<FIRST>r a AM-Marshall-CivilRights     09-09 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marshall-Civil Rights,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Marshall Says Court Risks Civil Rights of All Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall told a
group of federal judges Friday that recent high court decisions are
a risk to the civil rights of all citizens _ not just the rights of
minorities.
   Marshall said the court has ``come full circle'' back to the days
before its 1954 decision in Brown vs. Board of Education ended an
era of legal segregation, The New York Times reported in its
Saturday editions.
   Marshall made his remarks in Bolton Landing, N.Y., at an annual
meeting of federal judges from New York, Connecticut and Vermont. He
is the liaison officer for the judicial circuit in those states.
   ``It is difficult to characterize last term's decisions as the
product of anything other than a deliberate retrenching of the civil
rights agenda,'' Marshall said.
   Marshall dissented on several court rulings last term, including
decisions that make it more difficult to win lawsuits for employment
discrimination.
   Marshall said a restrictive approach to the rights of minorities
coincided with similar restrictions on the constitutional rights of
other groups, such as political dissenters.
   He said he feared that the rulings last term might pave the way
for the lowering of constitutional barriers separating church and
state.
   Referring to the court's change in its approach to civil rights,
Marshall said, ``We could sweep it under the rug and hide it, but
I'm not going to do it.''
   Marshall was concerned about the expansiveness of the court's
holdings, saying the court majority had gone beyond legal boundaries
of issues before the court to reach ``broad and wholly unnecessary''
conclusions.
</TEXT>
