<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0773 09-09 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0773,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Indicted in New York Racial Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with new attack in Bensonhurst.
ADDS 3 grafs to give details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old man who was among seven people
arrested in the slaying of a black teen-ager by a gang of white
youths last month was indicted Friday on murder, manslaughter and
other charges.
   A state grand jury charged Joseph Serrano with second-degree
murder for showing a ``depraved indifference to life'' in the
shooting death of Yusuf Hawkins, Brooklyn District Attorney
Elizabeth Holtzman told a news conference.
   Police, meanwhile, said Friday that three white men screaming
``Get out, Spanish,'' beat two Hispanic brothers in the
predominantly white Bensonhurst neighborhood, where the original
attack occurred. No arrests were made.
   Hawkins, 16, and three friends were attacked by about 30 young
whites, many carrying baseball bats, before the teen-ager was shot
Aug. 23. The four blacks had gone to Bensonhurst to look at a used
car.
   ``The killing of Yusuf Hawkins not only took the life of a young
man full of promise, it also sent shock waves throughout our city,''
Holtzman said.
   Of the six other Bensonhurst youths arrested in the attack, three
_ Joseph Fama, 18; Keith Mondello, 19; and Pasquale Raucci, 18 _
have been indicted on murder charges. Fama is accused of being the
triggerman.
   Serrano, speaking at his lawyers' office several hours after the
indictment was handed up, extended his sympathy to Hawkins' family
but said he was not part of the gang that killed him.
   ``As far as I am concerned I am being railroaded,'' said Serrano,
who could be sentenced to life in prison if convicted of murder.
   In addition to second-degree murder, Serrano was charged with
first-degree manslaughter, first-degree assault, riot, criminal
facilitation and criminal possession of a weapon, a loaded pistol.
He is not accused of actually shooting Hawkins.
   Serrano's attorney, James J. DiPietro, said the most serious
charge against Serrano when he surrendered to police Aug. 28 was
assault, and accused Holtzman of manipulating the grand jury to
obtain the murder charge in order to further her political career.
   Holtzman, a candidate for city comptroller, denied the allegation.
   Serrano remains free on $75,000 bail.
   The most recent victims in Bensonhurst, Enrique Andrade, 28, and
Luis Andrade, 22, were sitting on a bench on a street corner at 9:30
p.m. Thursday when they were approached by three white men,
estimated to be 16 to 21 years old.
   The whites shouted expletives and then screamed ``Get out,
Spanish'' as they punched, kicked and struck the men with a bottle,
said police spokesman Sgt. Maurice Howard.
   The brothers, who work as independent contractors and live in the
area, managed to run away. They were treated for cuts and bruises
and released from Coney Island Hospital, Howard said.
</TEXT>
