<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--TimesPrice     09-09 0105</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Times Price,0107</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daily Going to 40 Cents Sept. 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times will raise its weekday
newsstand price to 40 cents on Sept. 18. The Sunday edition will
stay at $1.25.
   The paper has been selling for 35 cents for a year and had been
30 cents the previous 6{ years.
   The increase, applying to papers distributed within a 75-mile
radius of New York and on all of Long Island, was prompted by higher
production and distribution costs, the Times said Friday.
   The price of the newspaper's national edition, 50 cents daily and
$2.50 Sundays, was not changed.
</TEXT>
