<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Peace Bjt   09-09 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Peace, Bjt,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Unmoved by Talk of Peace Plan's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir insists his peace
initiative is not dead, but in the five months since he announced it
the plan has only fostered divisions among both Palestinians and
Israelis.
   Just this week, the proposal caused arguments within the
left-leaning Labor Party and a squabble between Shamir and Labor
leader Shimon Peres. It also led to public criticism by Shamir of a
member of his own Likud bloc, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens.
   All the arguments started with doves in the Labor Party declaring
that Shamir's peace initiative was stalled and might die if
something wasn't done to save it.
   ``They are wrong,'' Shamir said in an interview published Friday
in the Jerusalem Post. ``It was an illusion to think that such an
initiative ... can produce results in such a sort time, of a few
weeks, a few months.''
   He said he was still awaiting a positive response from
Palestinians in the occupied territories and from Arab nations to
his call for elections among Palestinians as a first step toward
negotiations on the final status of the occupied lands.
   But the arguments over his plan struck at what was supposed to be
its strength. Other than the elections, the plan offers nothing
specific to the Palestinians, who have carried on a revolt for
nearly 21 months against Israeli occupation.
   The plan's vagueness was designed to make it acceptable to both
sides of Israel's coalition government, Shamir's right-wing Likud
and center-left Labor. This worked, and the Cabinet accepted the
plan on May 14.
   But Palestinians immediately demanded that the elections lead
eventually to an independent Palestinian state in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967
Middle East war.
   They also insisted the Palestine Liberation Organization, which
Israel considers a terrorist group, be part of any peace talks.
   Israel asked Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's help in gaining
Palestinian support, but he first wanted answers to 10 questions
about the Israeli initiative.
   Two of these touched on the very points that divide Israel's
Cabinet: Will Israel give up occupied land to achieve peace? Will it
allow the 140,000 Arabs in east Jerusalem to vote?
   Likud refuses to give up any occupied land and rejects giving the
vote to Arabs in east Jerusalem, which was annexed by Israel after
its capture in 1967. Labor accepts the U.S-backed formula of trading
land for peace and maintains east Jerusalem Arabs should cast
ballots, but outside the city. This week's arguments within Labor _
among the party's hawks and doves _ have been over just these points.
   For his part, Shamir wants no specifics added to the election
proposal.
   To head off a challenge from the far-right in Likud, he accepted
a party resolution rejecting land in exchange for peace and any vote
for east Jerusalem Arabs. But he insisted this did not change his
proposal.
   On Friday, in his Post interview, Shamir chastised Foreign
Minister Arens for suggesting the refusal to allow the vote in east
Jerusalem was official policy. ``This doesn't mean anything,'' he
said of Arens' statement.
   The prime minister, however, is under increasing pressure to
provide more specifics to entice Palestinians into elections.
   Labor doves referred to Mubarak's 10 questions in their demand to
get the peace plan moving. Sources in Washington also said the U.S.
government may use the Egyptian president's plan to press Shamir to
be specific.
   The prime minister shows no signs of giving in, however. He said
Thursday on Israel's Arab television channel he was willing to wait
a long time for Palestinians to accept his initiative as it stands.
   ``They will not see another plan proposed by us or any change in
the plan,'' Shamir said. ``There can be 10 points or 20 points, but
I see nothing to this.''
   ``There is no question of a time limit,'' he added. ``That would
be ridiculous.''
</TEXT>
