<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Buildings     09-09 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Buildings,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Architects Hit Back at Prince Charles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stop criticizing the style of Britain's new
buildings and take a closer look at why British cities are so
decrepit and ugly, leading architects are telling Prince Charles.
   ``Attacks on architects in an almost physical way are not
conducive to sitting down and getting to the next stage,'' Peter
Carolin, professor of architecture-elect at Cambridge University,
said Friday.
   His challenge closed out a week in which modern architecture was
front-page news, with the heir to the throne having a book published
that dismissed some modern British buildings as ``Frankenstein
monsters.''
   Two of Charles' targets took advantage of an offer to reply, made
by British Broadcasting Corp.'s national television network.
   One was Sir Denys Lasdun, whose National Theater the prince
compared to a ``nuclear power station in the middle of London.''
   Lasdun defended his concrete construction and compared its wide
interior spaces with the great amphitheaters of ancient Greece.
Critics were looking too much at the outsides of buildings and not
enough at the comfort and pleasure within, he said.
   The second target was Colin St. John Wilson. The prince likened
his red-brick British Library, now under construction, to a secret
police headquarters.
   Wilson said he had related the library to its neighbor, the
Victorian train station of St. Pancras, and to the local housing,
and had done everything to give readers natural daylight for their
studies.
   The architects argued that Britain gets ugly buildings and dreary
cities because it is too mean to want buildings of beauty,
preferring the job done fast and cheap. They said the culprits are
usually developers and accountants looking for quick profits.
   The prince has been campaigning for five years for better
buildings and an improved environment. His book, ``A Vision of
Britain,'' sets out his 10 principles to govern building design.
They include harmony with the surroundings, a human scale and use of
local materials.
   The prince likes classical-style buildings with decoration. His
opponents say buildings must reflect their time.
   Many architects resent the high public profile given to Charles'
criticisms because of his privileged position, but the profession
congratulated him on starting a great public debate.
   Carolin said: ``I hope the prince will now stop talking so much
about purely superficial stylistic issues. ... We have got to turn
to the things that really influence our society _ the quality of
life, the prosperity of our cities and from that the prosperity of
the nation.''
   Maxwell Hutchinson, president of the Royal Institute of British
Architects, said the problem was not just ``all that office space,''
which Charles condemns for scarring the London skyline, but the ``1
million homes in this country unfit for human habitation.''
   Richard Rogers, Britain's leading high-technology architect,
contrasted London unfavorably with Paris.
   Paris has a center, the Pavillon de l'Arsenal, where the public
can inspect designs for the hundreds of building projects in the
French capital as it seeks to become the economic and cultural
powerhouse of Europe after the creation in 1992 of a single market
for the 12-nation European Economic Community.
   ``Winning the commercial battle for 1992 is a matter of life and
death,'' said Rogers, who designed the Pompidou arts center in Paris
and the soaring Lloyd's building in London's City financial district.
   ``London is in danger of losing its advantages and slipping its
position,'' he said. ``It is not trying hard enough to improve
itself, to think about what kind of city it ought to be, to make
itself attractive to the Japanese, the Americans, the Europeans and,
of course, to its citizens.''
   ``We have forgotten the art of creating cities. We don't think
enough about the way we want to live.''
</TEXT>
