<FIRST>r w PM-NixonImpeachment     09-09 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nixon Impeachment,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reid Says Impeacment Trial Of Federal Judge Is Waste Of Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Senate committee reviewing
evidence in the impeachment case of U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon
says two days of hearings were a waste of taxpayer money.
   The House unanimously voted to impeach Nixon on charges of lying
about his knowledge of a narcotics case involving the son of a
wealthy businessman who had sold Nixon lucrative oil properties.
   But Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said Friday that he had not heard
any evidence indicating that Nixon had done anything wrong.
   ``Unless I can be convinced otherwise in the next few days, I can
think of very few instances that were a bigger waste of taxpayers'
money,'' Reid said.
   The judge was convicted by a federal court on the perjury charges
and is serving a five-year prison term, but continues to collect his
$89,500 annual salary.
   Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., chairman of the 12-member committee
that will summarize the evidence for the full Senate, said the
senators would make up their own minds, but advised Nixon's lawyer
that he didn't need ``a parade of character witnesses'' when the
defense presents its case starting Tuesday.
   ``There has been substantial testimony already as to the good
character of Judge Nixon'' by the witnesses called by the House,
Fowler said.
   The dispute over Nixon's involvement in the narcotics case
revolves around whether a conversation he had with the local
prosecutor constituted a ``discussion'' of the case.
   The prosecutor, Paul ``Bud'' Holmes, testified that Nixon did not
influence the outcome because he had already arranged a plea bargain
for the defendant.
   Nixon told a grand jury he never discussed the case with the
prosecutor or influenced anyone as to it outcome.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., who is leading the House case against
Nixon said after Friday's session that the issue was simply whether
Nixon lied.
   ``This is a perjury case,'' he said. ``We've never pretended it
was anything else.''
   The case against Nixon, as described by witnesses Thursday and
Friday began as a probe into his business dealings with Wiley
Fairchild, 76, a wealthy oil man in Hattiesburg, Miss.
   In early 1980, the judge bought interest in wells from Fairchild
with money he borrowed from Fairchild to be paid back as the wells
began to produce.
   In August 1980, Fairchild's son, Drew, was arrested on charges
related to marijuana smuggling at the airport where he worked.
   Drew Fairchild arranged a plea bargain with federal authorities
and avoided prison time but later was indicted by a state grand jury.
   The elder Fairchild testified Thursday that he thought the state
indictment was an effort by Holmes to blackmail him into paying more
legal fees for his son.
   Wiley Fairchild said he called Nixon, whom he considered his
friend because of their oil dealings, and complained.
   Nixon then got together with Holmes and, according to Holmes'
testimony, said Wiley Fairchild had asked him ``to put in a good
word for his boy.''
   Since a plea bargain had already been reached, Holmes said he and
Nixon decided to call Wiley Fairchild.
   According to Fairchild's testimony, Nixon told him over the
phone, ``Everything is going to be handled to your satisfaction.''
   During Holmes' testimony early in the day Friday, Reid asked him
if he and Nixon weren't simply ``trying to ingratiate yourselves
with a rich man in your community by, in effect, doing nothing for
him?''
   Holmes said that was right.
   The articles of impeachment allege:
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case
against Drew Fairchild with Holmes.
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do
officially or unofficially with the Fairchild case and never
influenced anyone in the case.
   _Nixon undermined ``the integrity of the judiciary'' and
disobeyed the law by making 14 false or misleading statements during
an interview with federal investigators and in his sworn grand jury
testimony.
</TEXT>
