<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich     09-09 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Defends Use Of Staff For Clerical Work On Book</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich says he was
operating within House rules when he used his congressional staff to
perform clerical work on a book he wrote in 1984.
   ``What we did was entirely, precisely appropriate,'' the Georgia
Republican said Friday in response to allegations made by a former
staffer in the October issue of the magazine, Mother Jones.
   In the magazine article, Dolores Adamson said she resigned from
Gingrich's district staff in 1983 after returning from a vacation to
find that Gingrich had put the district office staff to work copying
the book.
   ``In my mind, it was illegal,'' Ms. Adamson was quoted as saying.
   Gingrich said his staff did copying, proofreading and other
clerical tasks on his book, ``Window of Opportunity.'' But he said
House rules permit such activity as long as the book deals with a
public policy issue _ which he insisted his book did _ and the
staffers work at least 40 hours a week on congressional duties.
   House Democrats have filed a complaint with the ethics committee
alleging that Gingrich violated House rules and federal campaign
laws by creating an unusual partnership to promote the book. But the
complaint does not accuse Gingrich of any improprieties in the use
of his staff to work on the book.
   The committee has hired the Chicago law firm of Richard J. Phelan
to review the complaint and recommend whether it should launch a
formal investigation.
   Phelan was the ethics committee's independent counsel in the
investigation of former Speaker Jim Wright. Gingrich said Phelan's
investigation supports his contention that House rules permit
members of Congress to use staffers to work on books dealing with
public policy.
   One of the allegations against Wright was that he used members of
his congressional staff to help put together his book, ``Reflections
of a Public Man.'' Gingrich said Phelan ``specifically exonerated
Wright'' on that charge.
   Gingrich, who filed the ethics complaint that led to the
investigation and eventual resignation of Wright, disclosed last
year that his former administrative assistant, Frank Gregorsky,
reviewed and edited the book.
   But he said Friday that Gregorsky actually had left his staff by
the time he began working on the book.
   ``To the best of my knowledge,'' he said, the only work his
congressional staff did on the book ``was purely clerical stuff.''
   ``I did the entire initial draft,'' he said. ``We didn't delegate
all that stuff. We're talking about whether or not somebody helped
(copy) things. ... All the rewrite was done at private expense, by a
private coauthor who got paid a royalty and got paid in advance by a
private publisher.''
</TEXT>
