<FIRST>r a PM-Names     09-09 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Burt Reynolds' idea to expand
business at his ranch is causing some disagreement.
   Reynolds wants a zoning change for the B.R. Ranch, where he lives
and has a feed store, souvenir shop and petting farm.
   His plan to add a gas station and car wash, double the size of
the souvenir shop and build shops and offices was approved by a Palm
Beach County advisory panel Thursday.
   County site planner James Youngblood said the zoning change is
appropriate for the site in rural Jupiter. Earlier, a county staff
report called the planned development ``too intense'' and said it
would ``create a lone commercial pocket'' in a rural area.
   County commissioners will consider the plan at a public hearing
Oct. 2.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  Former New York Jets star Mark
Gastineau is leading a wave of the future as he and his
actress-girlfriend Brigitte Nielsen join the board of directors of
the B.C. Lions, says new owner Murray Pezim.
   Pezim, predicting the Lions will some day be members of the
National Football League rather than the Canadian Football League,
said Friday he is negotiating with others who have NFL experience.
He would not release their names.
   ``I think that in three or four years the NFL will be here and I
want to have the right people at the right time,'' he said.
   Gastineau, who was a defensive end and a five-time NFL all-pro,
announced last month he will train in Vancouver as he embarks on a
heavyweight boxing career. Pezim will act as his business manager.
   The role of Nielsen was less clear, with Pezim saying she ``will
represent the women's side of things.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GUAYAQUIL, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Britain's Princess Anne walked
narrow and dusty streets and opened a health clinic for the poor on
the third day of her visit to Ecuador.
   Curious residents looked on as the princess on Friday made her
way among houses made of cane, some suspended above stagnant ponds.
   Princess Anne was accompanied by British diplomats and officials
of the suburb of Guasmo, which has 500,000 people and is the poorest
area in Ecuador.
   Shortly before visiting the area, she assisted at the opening of
Dolorosa Clinic, which operates with economic assistance from the
royal family.
   On her arrival in Guayaquil, Ecuador's major port and largest
city, Mayor Elsa Bucaram presented her with the keys to the city.
   She planned to visit the Amazon jungle region during the weekend.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUELVA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Cristina, the youngest daughter of
King Juan Carlos, christened a replica of the Spanish caravelle
Pinta, which will sail with replicas of the two other ships used by
Christopher Columbus for his voyage to the New World in 1492.
   The 24-year-old princess took part in a ceremony Friday in this
southern Atlantic port city near where Columbus began his trip.
   The 90-ton oak vessel, constructed at a cost of $565,000, is the
first of three to be completed for the 500th anniverary celebration
of Columbus' voyage and the Expo '92 World's Fair to be held in
Seville.
   The Nina is under construction in Cartagena and the Santa Maria
is being built in Barcelona.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis helped honor 28 Southeast Asian
refugee women trained as child care workers.
   The wife of Gov. Michael Dukakis said Friday that the training
program, created by the Massachusetts Office for Refugees and
Immigrants, will help other Southeast Asian women get and keep jobs.
   ``Leaving a child in day care with strangers goes against
everything a mother is taught in Southeast Asian culture. As a
result, many of these women stay at home with their children and
turn to welfare to make ends meet, all because culturally
appropriate child care has been unavailable,'' Mrs. Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister
Toshiki Kaifu wound up a three-country North American tour with a
commitment to examine all environmental issues, said the premier of
British Columbia.
   ``That's not to say we'll solve all of the problems, but let's
begin. I think he's really behind it,'' Premier Bill Vander Zalm
said Friday.
   Kaifu was to fly to Tokyo today after completing a six-city,
three-country North American tour that included four days in Canada.
</TEXT>
