<FIRST>r w PM-Democrats-Bush     09-09 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Democrats-Bush,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Challenges Bush To Say How He'd Pay For New Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell says the
gap between President Bush's ``words and deeds'' is growing, and
that the president says too little about how he'll pay for major
initiatives.
   ``We saw it on space. The president wants to go to Mars, but
there is no plan, no timetable, no price given,'' the Maine Democrat
said.
   In a wide-ranging interview with a group of reporters Friday,
Mitchell said Bush advocates bold new programs but seems to want
Congress to worry about how to finance them.
   Mitchell said, for instance, that Bush provided too little help
for Congress in recommending how money could be moved around in the
fiscal 1990 budget to cover the $716 million the president wants to
spend beyond what was initially envisioned for anti-drug abuse
efforts.
   Bush earlier in the week called such questions ``carping'' and
challenged Democrats to back his plan.
   ``I think that what is going to happen is that the appeal of the
president's position is going to erode,'' Mitchell said. ``The gap
between his rhetoric and action, words and deeds, continues to
grow.''
   Mitchell said he didn't know how long Bush could uphold his 1988
campaign pledge against any general tax increases, but said the
Democrats won't make ``a cavalry charge'' for such increases without
his support.
   Mitchell said lawmakers already are struggling to pass 13
appropriations bills to carry out the $1.17 trillion budget
blueprint agreed upon earlier for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   ``This is a really tough task,'' he said. ``We've reached an
agreement almost universally criticized as being inadequate and not
going far enough, and that hasn't even been enacted.''
   Unless lawmakers find a way to cut next year's projected deficit
to $110 billion by Oct. 15, the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law
will automatically trigger spending cuts in many programs.
   ``So we face these constant and, it seems, accelerating,
pressures'' to reduce the federal deficit and ``deal with these
emerging demands,'' Mitchell said.
   He said he doubts the House and Senate will meet an Oct. 1
deadline for passing the money bills _ as the two chambers did last
year for the first time in 12 years.
</TEXT>
