<FIRST>r w PM-ConsumerCredit     09-09 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Credit,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Predict Slower Rate of Borrowing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans will continue to borrow for the
remainder of the year but at a slower pace, analysts say after a
government report that consumer debt fell in July for the first time
in 2{ years.
   ``Consumer borrowing has slowed down and will continue to be
slower than it was for two reasons,'' Larry Chimerine, senior
economic adviser for the WEFA Group in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said Friday.
   One reason is that consumer spending is weaker, particularly on
durable goods, big-ticket items that people generally finance with
loans, Chimerine said.
   ``And secondly, the high debt levels for many families has
discouraged people from borrowing more and, even when they spend,
they are being forced to pay more cash,'' he said.
   The Federal Reserve reported Friday that consumer debt in July
fell $280 million, a seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent annual rate of
decline. It was the first drop since borrowing fell 3.4 percent, or
$1.63 billion, in January 1987.
   Although it increased, borrowing also was slower in June than
previously thought, the Fed said. The pace was revised downward
Friday from 5.1 percent to 4.7 percent, or $2.72 billion.
   Sandra Shaber, an economist with The Futures Group here, said the
decline in borrowing in July, although temporary, reflects a
cautious consumer.
   She said consumer credit should pick up, but added, ``I don't
think we should expect any major boom in consumer spending.''
   Ms. Shaber noted that automobile sales, which were down in June,
had begun to rise in July and advanced a ``hefty amount'' last
month, so August consumer credit should be expected to increase.
   But many analysts don't expect the August pace to continue
because it was driven in large part by end-of-model-year incentives
and announced 1990-model price increases.
   Auto loans, which represent a major portion of consumer debt,
fell in July for the second straight month, down 6 percent after a
2.3 percent decline in June.
   The Fed said auto loans dropped $1.46 billion in July after
falling $549 million in June. Auto loans had risen 4.5 percent in
May and 3.3 percent in April.
   Borrowing for mobile homes declined for the sixth straight month,
down $60 million or 3 percent on an annual basis.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate also
dropped, $26 million or 0.2 percent on an annual basis. That
compared with advances of 2.5 percent in June and 7.2 percent in May.
   The only category to show an increase was revolving credit, which
includes credit cards, but even that rose at a slower pace than in
previous months.
   The Fed said revolving credit rose 8 percent, to $1.27 billion.
It had advanced 20.1 percent in June and 13 percent in May.
   The various changes left total consumer debt in July at a
seasonally adjusted $700.57 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
