<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Diplomats-Credentials     09-09 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Diplomats-Credentials,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Envoys' Union Sues State Department over Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union that represents career diplomats is
taking legal steps to combat what it calls a disturbing pattern by
the White House of appointing incompetents to key ambassadorships.
   The American Foreign Service Association filed suit Friday in
U.S. District Court, naming Secretary of State James A. Baker III as
the defendant.
   The highly unusual move follows the nomination by the White House
of a number of envoys who have come under sharp criticism on grounds
they have neither the diplomatic skills nor background knowledge of
the countries where they are being sent.
   Some Democrats charge that the nominations amount to political
payoffs for Republicans who contributed generously to the party in
last year's presidential campaign or demonstrated skill in raising
funds for the party.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., has described some of the choices as
``insulting.''
   The suit is the latest salvo in a long-simmering conflict in
which career diplomats often complain they are bypassed for
ambassadorial posts in favor political activists with dubious
qualifications.
   Among the nominees who have drawn the most complaints is Peter
Secchia, who helped President Bush carry Michigan last year and was
named ambassador to Italy. Many Italians were upset when he joked
that the new Italian Navy has glass-bottom boats ``so they can see
the old Italian Navy.''
   The New York Times complained in a July editorial that Bush's
nominee for Spain, Joseph Zappala, a Florida developer, has but one
claim to the Madrid assignment _ ``a distinctively large
contribution to the Republican Party, reportedly $126,000.''
   Senate confirmation of Zappala and two other nominees have been
delayed because of doubts about their credentials.
   The diplomats' union filed the suit to obtain release of
``Certificates of Competency'' that the law requires the president
to submit to the Senate on the qualifications of each nominee.
   The association said the State Department maintains the reports
are confidential and has refused to provide them to union officials.
   Since the information in the reports isn't ``classifiable,'' the
association said, they are being withheld ``only to avoid
embarrassment because they so clearly demonstrate the lack of
qualifications of many of the nominees.''
   Charles A. Schmitz, AFSA vice president, said that hiding
certificates from public view is self-defeating because they
routinely are made public after they reach the Senate, which must
confirm ambassadorial appointees for them to become effective.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, herself a
political appointee, cited the example of a 1970 nomination to
demonstrate the wisdom of some selections outside the Foreign
Service.
   She said that President Nixon chose a defeated candidate for the
Senate to be his ambassador at the United Nations, over the strong
objection of a ``major news publication.'' The appointee's name:
``George Herbert Walker Bush.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
