<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolClosed     09-09 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Closed,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambridge School for Black Students Closed by Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS HOPKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor and officials at a private
school for minority children claim that a group of neighbors helped
shut down the school for racially motivated reasons.
   Neighbors who signed a petition challenging the school's zoning
included chef Julia Child and constitutional scholar Laurence Tribe,
a Harvard Law School professor.
   ``They want peace and quiet at the expense of children and ethnic
people,'' said Mayor Alfred Vellucci, who also heads the school
committee, which had backed the private school. ``They don't want
anyone around while they smell the flowers.''
   Classes at the Commonwealth Day School were called off because
the petition led to a review of its zoning approval. School
officials could not guarantee the school would be open after next
week, when the state land court reviews its zoning status.
   Residents say they pressed for the repeal of zoning approval
because Commonwealth violates city zoning laws and causes traffic
congestion on a long, narrow street.
   Their attorney, Howard Medwed, denied racism was an issue.
   ``Some people are claiming racism is involved when there are far,
far different motives,'' Medwed said.
   He said the residents, some of whom own houses valued at more
than $1 million, were concerned for the peace and quiet of the
historic neighborhood.
   Commonwealth, which was founded in 1971, moved last September to
the building at Brattle Street that formerly housed the mostly white
New Preparatory School. Bert Giroux, of the city schools department,
said the high school was at the site for 50 years without major
complaints from residents.
   The petition said Commonwealth would come under different zoning
standards than the high school since it was for younger children.
   Commonwealth's headmaster, Robert Myette, said the zoning board
voted unanimously in October to grant permits to run the preschool
and elementary school.
   Jean Brooks, who lives next door to the school, solicited
signatures from more than 150 neighbors in the area and filed for an
appeal of the school's permits.
   Brooks said she doesn't believe the petition closed the school.
   ``They closed because they could not build up a large
constituency,'' she said.
   Several people affiliated with the school said the petition
played a major role in the closing.
   ``Through court orders, they choked the school economically,''
said Jack Gottlieb, whose 5-year-old daughter was one of seven white
students among the 50 students at the school. ``I think they didn't
like to see black little kids running around.''
   But some people said they were confused by the petition.
   Tribe said that when he was presented the petition he was told
the residents were trying to improve safety for the school children.
He said he was angered by the way the case turned out and that he
would investigate further.
   David Ives, president of WGBH, said he signed the Brooks petition
because of simple neighborly interest in zoning laws, and that he
knew nothing about the fate of the school in the matter.
   Julia Child was traveling to Massachusetts from California on
Friday and could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
