<NOTE>Report Says Mortgage Refinancing Rose This Summer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trade group says homeowners took advantage of
lower mortgage rates to refinance their loans this summer.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America, which surveyed 30 of
the nation's largest mortgage bankers, said Friday that all but one
company reported an increase in refinancing.
   The median rise in refinancing was 25 percent from early June to
late August and companies reported overall mortgage business up a
median 29 percent, the group said.
   Fixed-rate mortgages, which hit a peak of 11.22 percent in March,
fell to below 9.82 percent in mid-July and have risen since,
averaging 10.17 percent this week, according to the Federal Home
Loan Mortgage Corp.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Metal Detectors to Apply to Staff, Too</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional staffers will have to line up
with lobbyists, tourists, reporters and other visitors waiting to
pass through metal detectors at Senate office buildings.
   Only senators and U.S. Capitol Police officers are exempt from
the new security procedures that take effect Tuesday, Capitol Police
spokesman Dan Nichols said Friday.
   The move is part of a two-year effort to improve security,
Nichols said, and the same procedures will be applied to the three
House office buildings.
   In June, syndicated columnist Jack Anderson engineered the
smuggling of a gun into the Capitol building to point up lax
security. Nichols said the move to screen staffers was planned
before Anderson's escapade.
