<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0338EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     09-09 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Put Five Big S&amp;Ls Up for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are putting five more large
savings institutions up for sale, saying they hope to complete the
multibillion-dollar deals by the end of the month.
   The five, all with total assets of $9 billion, are in Texas,
Pennsylvania, Kansas, California and Florida.
   ``Due to the structure of the sales, we anticipate lengthy
negotiations with prospective investors should not be required,''
David C. Cooke, executive director of the Resolution Trust Corp.,
said Friday.
   The new agency, created last month to dispose of failed S&amp;Ls,
controls more than 270 thrift institutions. So far, it has closed 11
small S&amp;Ls, transferring their deposits to other institutions or
paying off customers directly.
   The RTC was originally planning to spend about $5 billion by the
end of this month on S&amp;L resolutions, but, with Friday's
announcement, is increasing the estimate to $8 billion, according to
agency spokesman Alan Whitney.
   The latest institutions offered are:
   _University Federal Savings Association, Houston, with $2.6
billion in assets and 362,890 deposit accounts.
   _Hill Financial Savings Association, Red Hill, Pa., with $2.6
billion in assets and 295,520 deposit accounts.
   _Peoples Heritage Savings, Salina, Kan., with assets of $1.8
billion and 101,268 deposit accounts.
   _Pacific Savings Bank, Costa Mesa, Calif., with assets of $1
billion and 46,898 deposit accounts.
   _Freedom Savings and Loan Association, Tampa, Fla., with $1
billion in assets and 148,102 deposit accounts.
