<FIRST>r w PM-CoffeeRequest     09-09 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coffee Request,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barco Asks Bush to Help Arrange Higher Coffee Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco is asking
President Bush for help in supporting higher coffee prices, the
White House says.
   Colombian coffee growers have been hard hit by recent price
declines, and some analysts worry that at least some might be
tempted to switch to coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine.
   Coca can produce far higher profits per acre than any other crop.
   U.S. support for higher coffee prices would represent a switch
from the U.S. position in international negotiations for a renewal
of key provisions of an international agreement on coffee marketing.
   ``President Barco did communicate on this issue,'' spokesman
Roman Popadiuk said Friday night. ``We are studying the issue
carefully.''
   He declined to give details about Barco's request.
   Colombian cocaine gangs, the source of 80 percent of the drug
consumed in the United States, and the government are engaged in a
bitter battle over the cocaine trade. Hundreds of judges,
journalists and other officials have been murdered by the drug
traffickers.
   As a result of a breakdown of negotiations in July, the 74-nation
International Coffee Organization suspended export quotas for member
nations for the third time in its 26-year history.
   The United States and some producing nations opposed quotas
during the negotiations.
   The July 1 price of about $1.20 per pound for unroasted beans,
the floor target price of the organization, fell to 80 cents by the
end of the month. It now stands at about 85 cents.
</TEXT>
