<FIRST>r p PM-NewYorkElection     09-09 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New York Election,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Observers Will Watch Polls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Justice Department observers will monitor
Tuesday's mayoral primaries to protect minority voters' rights,
members of a coalition that had requested federal intervention said.
   The announcement Friday came on the heels of a new poll showing
Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins slightly ahead of Mayor
Edward I. Koch in the four-candidate Democratic primary.
   The announcement was made by state Assemblyman Jose Serrano of
the Bronx and the Center for Constitutional Rights, members of the
coalition of elected officials and residents.
   ``The basis for our request was the manner in which the New York
City Board of Elections conducted the April 19, 1988, presidential
primary,'' Randolph M. Scott-McLaughlin, a law professor at Pace
University in White Plains, said in a statement issued by the center.
   ``In that election, thousands of minority voters were
disenfranchised when they were improperly purged from the election
rolls, election machines broke down repeatedly and minority voters
were discouraged, deterred and in some instances coerced from
exercising their right to vote.
   ``Out of a fear that this conduct would once again occur, we
sought federal intervention,'' Scott-McLaughlin said.
   He said the center was told Friday by David Marblestone, an
attorney in the Justice Department's voting rights section, that
observers would be coming to New York.
   Marblestone referred calls from The Associated Press to Justice
Department spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade, who said it is the
government's policy not to comment on voting observers until the day
before they are sent.
   A federal observer with broad powers under the Voting Rights Act
will be stationed in the city and a team of observers and lawyers
will visit polling places, the center said.
   In the Daily News-Eyewitness News poll of 280 Democrats likely to
vote in the primary, Dinkins was ahead of Koch 47 percent to 43
percent. The other two Democratic candidates, Comptroller Harrison
J. Goldin and Richard Ravitch, got 4 percent and 2 percent
respectively. Four percent were undecided.
   Koch and Dinkins were considered statistically even because the
margin of error, 6 percentage points, was greater than the gap
between the two.
   Nine out of 10 blacks surveyed said they would vote for Dinkins,
who is black, a 20 percentage-point gain over a July poll.
   In the Republican primary, former U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani
faces Ronald Lauder, a former U.S. ambassador to Austria. Giuliani
is also on the Liberal Party line and Lauder is also on the
Conservative Party ballot.
   The Daily News and Eyewitness News, WABC-TV's nightly news show,
plan to release their poll Sunday on the Republican contest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
