<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Considers Giving $3 Million to Ortega's Election Opponent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will ask for up to $3
million for the political campaign of an opponent of Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega, according to a report published today.
   The administration had been considering using the CIA to affect
the election in Nicaragua, but now is leaning toward using the
donation to the campaign of Violeta Chamorro because it wouldn't
draw as much fire from Congress, The Washington Post reported.
   The February election is seen by the Bush administration as an
opportunity to end the rule of Ortega's Marxist-led Sandinista
government.
   The money would be drawn from the National Endowment for
Democracy, an organization created by Congress in 1982 to support
democratic processes worldwide, the Post reported.
   Under Nicaraguan law, half the money donated to a political
candidate from outside the country must be handed over to the
Supreme Election Council. The Supreme Election Council is supposed
to use that money to help defray costs of the election.
   But that law means if the United States will have to donate a
total of $6 million to ensure that $3 million goes into the
Chamorro's campaign treasury, the Post reported, citing unnamed
sources.
