<SECOND>PM-Yeltsin,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Firebrand Yeltsin Heading to U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist maverick Boris N. Yeltsin, who became a
folk hero for standing up to the Kremlin, is to spend a week in the
United States and meet with members of Congress and businessmen,
Radio Moscow reported.
   The official radio station said he was to depart today and arrive
in New York in the afternoon.
   In its report, Radio Moscow said Yeltsin favors ``drastic
reforms'' and that according to polls he is second only to President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in popularity. Radio Moscow did not give
details of the polls.
   Yeltsin, 58, once was a close protege of Gorbachev as Moscow
party boss. But he was fired after an October 1987 speech in which
he criticized Politburo conservative Yegor K. Ligachev and said
reforms were giving the people little.
   Yeltsin rocketed back into the forefront with a landslide victory
in parliamentary elections in March, and was elected to the Supreme
Soviet legislature a few months later in a deft political comeback.
He now heads a parliamentary committee on construction.
   Radio Moscow said he plans to use his trip to the United States
to familiarize himself with the Congress and determine whether its
operations can be applied to the Supreme Soviet.
   Yeltsin has become a populist for demanding an end to the
privileges of the Soviet elite and heads an organized opposition
group in the parliament.
