<FIRST>r a PM-SymphonyHall     09-09 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Symphony Hall,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Van Cliburn Plays at Grand Opening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARRYL EWING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World-renowned pianist Van Cliburn was the featured
performer at Friday's opening of the Morton H. Meyerson Symphony
Center, but the $81.5 million complex stole the show.
   ``I think the hall has a presence and this is something that's
important no matter what little tuning will go on,'' Cliburn said
during an intermission Friday. ``It's very hard to put in a
presence, but I think the hall has a presence, and that's
important.''
   A capacity crowd of more than 2,000 packed the hall to hear
Cliburn, a Fort Worth pianist, and the Dallas Symphony Orchestra
perform Tchaikovsky's ``Piano Concerto No. 1.''
   Architect I.M. Pei designed the hall as a series of overlapping
geometric shapes. The rectangular structure sits at an angle inside
a square, surrounded by segments of circles. The Dallas Museum of
Art and the Dallas skyline are visible through $6 million worth of
glass panes that make a sweeping curve of the lobby.
   The hall includes a 4,463-pipe organ, Italian marble and
artificially weathered limestone.
   U.S. House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said the hall
sends a message to the world that Dallas is determined to be a
leader in the arts.
   ``I think the real meaning of all of this is that Dallas and its
people have the capacity to build and succeed at a time that has not
been economically good to do so,'' he said.
   Conductor Eduardo Mata said the hall's opening was a historic
moment for the Dallas Symphony Orchestra and the city.
   ``This shows what people can do if they work together and work
hard,'' Mata said after Friday's concert. ``I'm sure this hall will
set the standard for years to come.''
   Even though it has been trumpeted as a world-class music hall,
the center is not without critics.
   They contend Dallas city leaders have ``misplaced priorities,''
and should have poured much of the money spent on the hall into road
repair, education and expanded police and fire protection.
</TEXT>
