<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0522EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     09-09 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-North Korean Army General Says Kim Il Sung Started Korean War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former North Korean deputy army chief
of staff and ambassador to the Soviet Union said today that North
Korean leader Kim Il Sung started the Korean War by ordering an
invasion of South Korea.
   ``The Korean War was personally ordered by Kim Il Sung and I can
testify on details,'' said Lee Sang Jo, 74, who defected to the
Soviet Union in 1961.
   ``Considering the fact that Seoul fell to the North Korean army
only three days after the war began, it is beyond question who
started the Korean War,'' the former North Korean army general said.
   Lee, now a naturalized Soviet citizen, said he came to South
Korea on Tuesday to visit relatives in his hometown of Pusan on the
southern coast.
   After a courtesy call on Park Chul-un, a Cabinet minister without
porfolio, Lee said he planned to hold a news conference next week to
discuss the Korean War and his relations with Kim Il Sung.
   Lee, as a lieutenant general, was North Korea's deputy army chief
of staff when the war broke out on June 25, 1950.
   The North Korean army, backed by Soviet tanks, invaded and
overran most of South Korea in less than three months but was
repelled by allied U.N. forces led by U.S. Gen. Douglas MacArthur.
   After Chinese volunteer forces intervened on the side of North
Korea, the war became stalemated, forcing both sides to start talks
to halt the conflict.
   In the armistice talks with U.N. forces, Lee served as the deputy
North Korean delegate. He later replaced Gen. Nam Il as the chief
communist negotiator in the talks. The fighting ended July 27, 1953,
but the two countries are still technically at war.
   Lee defected to the Soviet Union after serving as North Korea's
ambassador to Moscow from 1957 to 1960. He said his defection was to
avoid Kim Il Sung's mass purge of political enemies.
   Lee's trip to Seoul reflects warming relations between South
Korea and the Soviet Union. The countries have no diplomatic
relations but have expanded non-political contacts significantly in
recent years. They exchanged trade offices early this year.
</TEXT>
