<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0528EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Shrimpers-Protests     09-09 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shrimpers-Protests,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Cool Off; Bush to Review Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry shrimpers who blockaded a waterway
cooled off after hearing that President Bush agreed to review
regulations requiring them to use turtle excluder devices in their
nets.
   ``We gave them 10 days, 10 days we told those guys. We have to
hear something before then. We want to hear that instead of hurting
the people and spending tax money that they're going to start a
hatchery for those turtle eggs and raise them. That's what they need
to do, not hurt us,'' said shrimper Emery Eymard.
   The Coast Guard said 37 vessels took part in the day-long
blockade on Friday in south Louisiana, but protesting shrimpers
estimated between 50 and 100 big, double-rigged boats barricaded the
industrial pass.
   The blockade ended at 5 p.m. after the Coast Guard relayed word
from U.S. Rep. Billy Tauzin, D-La., that Bush had agreed to review
the regulations. Bush met with Tauzin, U.S. Reps. Lindy Boggs,
D-La., and Bob Livingston, R-La., during his visit to New Orleans
Friday.
   ``We received the president's commitment to look into the
Commerce Department decision on Monday,'' Tauzin said. He said that
John Sununu, Bush's chief of staff, will meet with Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher.
   No arrests were made Friday and no violence was reported, said
Coast Guard Cmdr. William Loeftstedt. Authorities, however, did take
down names and boat registrations of the protesting shrimpers.
   About 500 demonstrating shrimpers from Louisiana, Mississippi,
Alabama and Florida carried picket signs along Bush's motorcade
route in New Orleans.
   The blockade on the water formed at Belle Pass near Grand Isle
Friday morning, a few hours after the regulations requiring the use
of the TEDs took effect, the Coast Guard said. Some of the vessels
flew the skull and crossbones; others flew American flags upside
down, a distress signal.
   More than 30 boats were unable to get through the pass, which is
used mostly by shrimpers and oil company boats, Coast Guard Cmdr.
Dave Smith said.
   Another 30 to 40 shrimpers blocked the Intracoastal Waterway near
Intracoastal City, La., said Chief Petty Officer Glenn LaMont. No
arrests were made at the remote location near the center of
Louisiana's coastline, he said.
   An estimated 11,000 sea turtles die each year in Gulf Coast
shrimp nets, including the endangered Kemp's ridley, leatherneck and
hawksbill and the threatened loggerhead and green sea turtles.
   The cagelike TEDs fit in the back section of a shrimp trawl. A
grid across the middle allows shrimp to flow through but catches
turtles. Waterflow through the device helps turtles escape via a
trap door.
   Shrimpers say they lose 10 percent to 30 percent of their shrimp
through the TEDs. Commerce officials say side-by-side tests have
shown losses of 2 percent to 5 percent.
   Mosbacher had tried allowing shrimpers to limit their trawling
times to 105 minutes, with the idea that most turtles wouldn't drown
in that time. But the method was found to be ineffective.
   Failure to use TEDs could result in a maximum $20,000 fine, but
the Commerce Department will phase in its enforcement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890909-0042 </DOCNO>
