<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-AIDS     09-09 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-AIDS,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Orders AIDS Patients Isolated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi has ordered
health officials to identify and isolate AIDS patients to try to
prevent the spread of the deadly virus, according to newspaper
reports today.
   Moi claimed some AIDS patients had ``vowed not to die alone but
to take along with them to the grave scores of others.'' He cited a
case in which he said one victim deliberately infected 100 other
people, according to reports in Kenya's three daily English-language
newspapers.
   The president asked the minister of health, Mwai Kibaki, to
determine how many of the 6,000 known sufferers of AIDS in this East
African nation were Kenyans and how many were foreigners, and to
isolate them, the newspapers said.
   Moi did not elaborate further. He made the comments Friday at a
fund-raising meeting in Karatina, 90 miles north of Nairobi.
   There is no known cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
which destroys the body's immune system and with that its ability to
fight disease.
</TEXT>
