<FIRST>r a PM-Martinez     09-09 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Martinez,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Documents Paint Portrait of Competitive Drug Money-Laundering Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haggling over percentage points representing
thousands of dollars in commissions for laundering drug money was
common in the world of the the Medellin cocaine cartel's financial
director, court documents indicate.
   An affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta by Drug
Enforcement Administration agent Albert D. Latson chronicles part of
the government's 2{-year undercover investigation of the cartel. It
portrays Eduardo Martinez Romero as having a role in laundering tens
of millions of dollars through U.S. and Panamanian banks.
   Martinez, 36, remained in custody Friday under tight security on
federal money-laundering and fraud charges after his extradition
from Colombia. He was flown to Atlanta early Thursday and faces a
Monday court hearing.
   Martinez, who told a federal judge in a preliminary hearing
Thursday that he has a graduate degree in marketing, bargained with
undercover DEA agents during a secretly videotaped meeting in March
1988 on the Caribbean island of Aruba, according to the Latson's
affidavit.
   The undercover operation, based in Atlanta, used DEA agents to
act as Americans interested in laundering cocaine profits from
Colombia.
   A typical transaction worked this way, according to the court
documents: money would be delivered to a ``financial broker'' in the
United States, who then took it to one of several companies, some
legitimate and some false.
   The company would deposit the cash under its name and then send
the now ``clean'' money by wire transfer to a second bank account
controlled by Banco de Occidente in Panama.
   Typically, those banks were in New York and Los Angeles, but
Martinez told the agents that Banco de Occidente wanted to open an
account in an Atlanta bank in hopes of the money being delivered
faster.
   Banco de Occidente would have the funds transferred to Panama to
accounts controlled by Martinez, according to the affidavit.
   Delays in getting the money moving cost the cartel in lost
interest and made it more likely that U.S. authorities would have an
opportunity to seize the funds.
   As the agents attempted to get Martinez' business, he compared
them to a Uruguayan group known as La Mina, a precious metals
exporter but also known to federal prosecutors as another drug money
launderer, Latson said in the document.
   La Mina, Martinez told the agents, charged 7 percent per
transaction, but the undercover agents' organization would cost him
8 percent _ and he wanted a discount. Martinez also was taped saying
La Mina could launder huge amounts of money in only 48 hours.
   Go-betweens and couriers working for the launderers could make
thousands of dollars per transaction _ $44,710 for a $1.035 million
deal in December 1987; $109,514 for $1.5 million in January 1988,
for example.
   At an earlier meeting in Panama, Martinez told the agents that if
something goes wrong with the process, an unidentified ``they''
would kidnap and interrogate those involved and retaliate ``if the
answers were not satisfactory,'' Latson said in his affidavit.
   Eventually, the affidavit said, the agents reached an agreement
with Martinez to launder some of the Medellin cartel's money,
including a series of transactions in February and March of this
year involving some $6.2 million.
   The La Mina group was indicted earlier this year in Los Angeles
on money-laundering charges stemming from the same investigation
that snared Martinez, Operation Polar Cap.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890909-0044 </DOCNO>
