<FIRST>r a PM-WillieB     09-09 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Willie B,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alas, Bachelor Gorilla Succeeds with 6-Year-Old Female</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B. has shown there is hope for even the
most sheltered bachelors of the world.
   Zoo Atlanta's famous lowland gorilla _ who spent almost three
decades alone in a cage _ mated Friday with a 6-year-old female in
front of his stunned trainer and visiting children who hadn't
expected to see such monkey business.
   ``What better way to have an introduction to life,'' said Amy
Gross, a zoo visitor.
   Zoo officials thought it would be at least another year before
the 31-year-old gorilla, well, did what comes naturally.
   ``We're just excited he has shown us he knows what to do,'' said
Dr. Terry Maple, the zoo's director. ``He's not as bad off as we
thought.''
   Kinyanni, Willie's newly matured partner, and the longtime
bachelor had been ``wrestling and chasing each other'' since they
were placed together about two months ago, said Charles Horton,
Willie's longtime trainer.
   But Friday, Horton walked by and Willie ``had his arm up on her
shoulder; she had a hand on him, and they were touching each
other,'' he said.
   Horton said Willie followed Kinyanni around but grabbed her when
she decided to walk away. Kinyanni stepped toward Willie, Horton
said, and Willie answered the call of the wild.
   Zoo officials said the tryst lasted about two hours.
   ``It was totally unbelievable to see this,' Horton said. ``It was
astonishing to see. ... I hope he keeps on doing this.''
   Willie has progressed quickly since May 1988, when he stepped
outdoors for the first time since he was captured in the wild at
about age 3.
   Researchers say they will wait about a month to see whether
Willie and Kinyanni produce offspring. Willie's sperm count has been
deemed a little low.
   Later Friday, the lovers had another romantic encounter.
   Some zoo visitors were surprised. Others were embarrassed, but
not Jerry Hymanson of Atlanta, who seemed proud of Willie's progress.
   ``At 31 years old, don't you think it's about time?'' he said.
</TEXT>
