<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0619EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bioethics-Lawmakers     09-09 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bioethics-Lawmakers,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bioethic Meeting Speaker Says Lawmakers Shirking Duty on Life-Death
Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's lawmakers are sidestepping crucial
decisions on when life begins and when it should end despite medical
advances on both issues, a judge told a conference of doctors,
judges and ethicists.
   ``The other branches of government by and large refuse to accept
their responsibility,'' Washington, D.C., Superior Court Judge
Gladys Kessler said Friday. ``These issues do not have a consensus
in society.''
   She said apparently lawmakers believe that ``the waters are too
turbulent'' to take strong stands on the life-and-death issues.
   Kessler told the National Judicial College Bioethics Conference
that most laws nationwide say the state ``has an absolute right to
preserve life.'' But few laws have been passed that take into
account fine legal distinctions that have developed as people live
longer and survive illnesses that would have killed them just a
decade ago.
   ``How can we avoid the harder and most emotion-laden issue of the
quality of life?'' she asked some 150 conferees from across the
country.
   Chief justices nationwide were invited to send two judges to the
conference at the nation's premiere school for judges on the
University of Nevada, Reno campus.
   Twenty national organizations, including the American Medical
Association and the National Bar Association, also were asked to
send two delegates each to the meeting.
   ``We wanted to hold the conference because these issues must be
discussed to come up with some answers that judges can take back to
their states,'' said Thomas Russell, associate dean of the college.
``The courtroom usually is the place of last resort for these
medical-ethical issues to be resolved.''
   Ms. Kessler was joined Friday by Ruth Purtilo,
ethicist-in-residence at Massachusetts General Hospital, in
explaining to conferees the latest bioethical dilemmas.
   ``Everybody's thinking about ethics these days ... it's almost a
national pastime,'' Ms. Purtilo said. ``We have a complete society
that's worrying.
   ``We all are in a new neighborhood of thought, of deliberations.
People are living longer and surviving longer because of medical
technology. ... It's the stuff of science fiction, but it's here.''
   Ms. Purtilo told doctors and judges they must not only consider
medical facts surrounding the case, but also review what's best for
patients, families and, in some cases, the unborn.
   In doing that, Ms. Purtilo warned that often there would be more
than one wrong and one right answer to a dilemma and judges and
doctors would be forced to make such life-and-death decisions
``under terrible pressures of time.''
   ``We as a society have to understand that the patient's voice
must be heard,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890909-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0636EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-Missionary     09-09 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Missionary,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Missionary Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American missionary was deported after
Kenya's chief immigration official told him he should have left last
year when his organization was banned, the missionary's daughter
said today.
   Richard Hamilton of Medford, Ore., boarded a Kenya Airways flight
to London Friday night after spending about 24 hours in the custody
of Kenyan officials, said his daughter, Carolee Laroi.
   ``We were told by the (U.S.) Embassy that he was sent out last
night,'' Mrs. Laroi said. ``We never heard from him.''
   An embassy official was prevented from seeing Hamilton at Kenya's
immigration department but caught up with him at the airport, she
said.
   ``They contacted us to tell him he was OK,'' she said.
   Hamilton, 51, was director of the East African Christian Mission
in Kenya.
   Kenya's chief immigration official, Frank Kwinga, on Friday said
Hamilton and his wife, Jane, should have left Kenya in July 1988
when their mission, which has been in Kenya 15 years, was banned.
   Mrs. Laroi said her mother was prepared to leave the country but
had not been officially contacted as of today.
   ``She's going to wait until they tell her to go,'' she said by
telephone from the Hamiltons' home in Kitale, about 215 miles
northwest of Nairobi, the capital.
   On Friday, Mrs. Hamilton said she believed her husband was being
used as a ``scapegoat'' in a local scandal.
   Hamilton was deported one day after being extensively questioned
about a meeting he had a week earlier with a controversial bishop of
the Anglican Church of the Province of Kenya.
   Mrs. Hamilton said the Kenyans apparently believed her husband
passed information to the bishop, Alexander Muge. Muge on Tuesday
claimed that a senior Kenyan civil servant skimmed 462,000 pounds of
maize from relief food destined for famine-stricken parts of
southern Sudan.
   Mrs. Hamilton and the bishop, contacted by telephone, denied
Hamilton had passed any such information to Muge during their
meeting.
   Mrs. Hamilton and Muge said the meeting concerned Hamilton's
interest in whether Muge's church would act as an umbrella
organization under which Hamilton's mission could be re-registered
with the government.
   The mission was ordered to close after a local official
complained to Nairobi authorities that he believed the Hamiltons
were allied with his political enemies, Mrs. Hamilton said.
   She said that although their work permits were consequently
invalidated, the couple appealed and received verbal assurances from
the attorney general and local officials that they could continue
their development work in the arid West Pokot region until the
appeal was decided.
   In November 1987, the Hamiltons were threatened with deportation
after the Kenyans accused them of involvement in an alleged Ku Klux
Klan-backed plot to overthrow the government of President Daniel
arap Moi. The alleged plot was later found to be a baseless threat
from a disgruntled Kenyan-born priest living in the United States.
   A year earlier, the Kenyans detained two Americans working at the
Hamiltons' mission and accused them of illegally trying to import
guns and radio transmitters. One of the detained missionaries, Lyle
Hutson, 63, also of Medford, had a heart attack and died while in
police custody.
   The mission said the suspect shipment included air rifles and air
pistols but no real weapons.

</TEXT>
