<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Argentina-Rights     09-09 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina-Rights,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT cycle designator to PMs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate Against Pardon for Military Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 30,000 people marched
through downtown Buenos Aires to protest possible presidential
pardons for military officers accused of torture and killings in the
1970s.
   The march Friday was the first large demonstration during the
2-month-old administration of President Carlos Menem, who is
considering pardons for officers accused of human rights violations
in the military's ``dirty war'' against leftists.
   The marchers trailed behind a huge banner reading, ``No Impunity
_ Trial and Punishment for the Guilty!'' Police said about 30,000
people participated.
   Menem called the march ``political'' and told reporters he
planned to resolve the ``military problem'' by the end of the year.
He provided no details.
   Speaking to reporters at Government House, Menem said Argentines
should ``begin working in the present for the future'' and ``set
aside the past, without forgetting it.''
   The demonstration was organized by human rights groups and some
leftist political parties, including a faction of Menem's
labor-based Peronist Party.
   ``The pardon Menem is promising the murderers is a way of showing
that justice does not exist in this country,'' said Hebe Bonafini,
president of the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo, a group of mothers
and relatives of people who disappeared during the anti-subversion
campaign and are presumed dead.
   Menem has said action is needed to end military-civilian tensions
growing out of the brutal campaign against suspected left-wing
subversives by military governments that ruled from 1976 until 1983.
   A government commission named by Menem's predecessor, former
President Raul Alfonsin, determined that at least 8,900 people
disappeared during that time.
   ``It is going to be very difficult for us to fulfill the
fundamental objective of growth and development with social justice
if we maintain permanently open wounds in the heart of our
community,'' Menem said Friday.
   Two separate military groups are involved in reports of possible
pardons.
   One includes about 30 middle-ranking army officers, headed by
Col. Mohamed Seineldin and Lt. Col. Aldo Rico, who face disciplinary
action for taking part in army uprisings in April 1987 and January
and December.
   The revolts, quelled with little bloodshed, were aimed at ending
the civilian-court trials of officers accused of human rights abuses
in earlier cases.
   In the second group are 17 army generals and two navy admirals
who face trial on charges that include murder, torture and
kidnapping.
   The Buenos Aires newspaper La Nacion quoted Menem on Friday as
saying he would order a pardon for the rebels when he returns from a
trip later this month to the United States.
   Officials have indicated that before the end of the year Menem
also would pardon the generals and admirals awaiting trial but not
not for six former members of the military junta and high-ranking
officers already convicted and sentenced.
</TEXT>
