<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0459 09-09 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Gabrielle Weaker, Pushing Toward Maritime Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `At 10:30 p.m. ...' to UPDATE location, speed;
Picks up 10th graf, `Meanwhile, Felix ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weakened Hurricane Gabrielle is pushing north
today in the open Atlantic Ocean toward Canada's Maritime provinces
after brushing by Bermuda and skirting the U.S. coast.
   Forecasters at the National Hurricane Center said late Friday
they expect Gabrielle to shift to the northeast over the weekend and
move away from the Canadian coast.
   ``The slowing down means (Gabrielle) is probably going to change
direction,'' said meteorologist Jim Gross. ``We're not forecasting
landfall.''
   But Gross said there is still a 10 to 15 percent chance Gabrielle
could move toward Nova Scotia or Newfoundland by late Monday.
   Meanwhile, Gabrielle was expected to gradually lose forward speed
and strength, he said.
   ``The swells are going to affect the eastern U.S. coast and the
Maritime provinces of Canada for some time,'' Gross said, ``at least
the next two days.''
   Swells up to 20 feet lashed at the eastern tip of Bermuda Friday,
where one house was damaged the day before. Marine traffic around
the island was halted as the storm produced 10-foot swells even in
harbors.
   At 6 a.m. EDT today, the center of Gabrielle was located near
38.4 north latitude and 60.0 west longitude, or about 400 miles
south of Sable Island, Nova Scotia.
   Gabrielle had 90 mph winds and was moving north at 10 mph. The
hurricane which earlier peaked at 135 mph was expected to keep
hurricane-strength winds of at least 74 mph through the weekend,
Gross said.
   Meanwhile, Felix, which has rumbled around the Atlantic as both a
storm and a weak hurricane, was headed on a northeastern course,
away from land, late Friday.
   The storm lost its tropical characteristics and would not merge
with Gabrielle, as both systems' earlier courses indicated, Gross
said.
   There have been five hurricanes in this Atlantic hurricane
season, which began June 1 and runs to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
