<FIRST>r a PM-BuildingCollapse     09-09 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Building Collapse,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Dead, Seven Injured When Packing Plant Mezzanine Collapses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mezzanine platform collapsed on workers in
a fruit packing warehouse, killing one woman and injuring seven
others, authorities said.
   Sharon Raschke of Yakima died after a portion of the balcony fell
on her as she was sorting fruit at a Hansen Fruit Co. warehouse
Friday afternoon, police said.
   Four other plant workers also were trapped beneath the debris
until freed by fire rescue crews in less than an hour, said fire Lt.
Al Chronister. Rescuers used inflatable bags and materials from an
adjacent lumber yard to lift the debris off the women, he said.
   Chronister said the survivors were lucky. ``There was some pretty
heavy stuff coming down,'' he said. He estimated the platform, which
was built into a wall, weighed several tons.
   There were 60 workers inside the concrete warehouse when the
accident occurred, said Barb Dunn of the state Department of Labor
and Industries in Olympia. State and local officials are
investigating.
   Two women were in serious condition at St. Elizabeth's Medical
Center, said hospital spokeswoman Kathy O'Meara-Wyman. They were
identified as Carolyn Storms, 47, and Barbara Gray, 62, both of
Yakima.
   Of the other injured workers, most were treated and released but
one woman, who is pregnant, was hospitalized for observation.
   Ms. Dunn said it was the first fatality in the state's
fruit-packing industry since the early 1970s, when such
record-keeping began. Hansen Fruit was inspected by the state last
June and no violations were found, she said.
   Hansen officials ordered reporters out of the building and
refused to answer questions.
</TEXT>
