<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0450 09-09 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Grills Cabinet Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with committee meetings resuming, quotes
from nominees, communist party, Walesa.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers today interviewed more Cabinet
nominees for a Solidarity-led government that would end four decades
of Communist control of foreign affairs, the news media and the
economy.
   Some nominees were questioned in Parliament about issues that had
long been virtually unmentionable, such as Soviet-Polish relations.
   Eight committees of the Sejm, or lower house of parliament, held
their first day of hearings Friday and gave a positive
recommendation to all but two of the nominees they questioned.
   Further sessions were planned through the weekend to get ready
for a vote Tuesday on the government proposed by Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki. Committee votes do not oblige Mazowiecki to
withdraw candidates.
   The candidates include 13 Solidarity members and four from the
Communist Party. The two independent political parties that helped
put Solidarity in power last month _ the United Peasant Party and
the Democratic Party _ have four and three nominees respectively.
   Gen. Florian Siwicki, the Communist nominated to remain as
defense minister, told one committee: ``The army is a pro-reform
institution.''
   Solidarity's Leszek Balcerowicz, nominated as vice premier and
minister of finance, outlined a program to rescue Poland's
hard-pressed economy that includes restructuring the tax system to
lower levies on profits while setting up a progressive personal
income tax and a sales tax.
   The program also includes controls on wage inflation,
liberalizing foreign trade rules, protecting the drain of goods and
capital from Poland, and unifying the official and ``commercial''
currency exchange rates, he said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa kept his distance from the
enactment of the historic changes his movement initiated.
   Interviewed late Friday upon returning from four days of meetings
in West Germany, he denied there was a danger of a two-front
government _ run by Mazowiecki in Warsaw and Walesa from his Gdansk
home.
   ``No, I am out,'' he told the government news agency PAP. ``I am
interested only in pluralism, freedom, democracy. And when
everything works, I am really going on vacation. I will not enter
the government.''
   The foreign minister nominee told lawmakers that Poles forced to
remain in the Soviet Union after World War II should be allowed to
return, PAP said.
   Krzysztof Skubiszewski, a little-known independent, also said
Poland's foreign policy must not be formulated any one political
party, the news agency said. He made the remarks to the legislative
committee responsible for contacts with Poles living abroad, which
along with the Foreign Affairs Committee voted in favor of his
nomination, PAP said.
   Thousands of Poles in the Soviet Ukraine and the Baltics,
particularly Lithuania, live in what was Polish territory until the
Soviets annexed it after the war. Some have demanded to be allowed
to travel more freely back to Poland. There was no immediate comment
by Soviet officials.
   PAP said Mazowiecki, elected Aug. 24 prime minister, nominated 19
people for posts Thursday and four Friday. He plans to present a
final list of nominees on Tuesday, when he outlines his government's
program in a speech.
   It appeared Solidarity would control 13 posts, including prime
minister, in the 24-member Council of Ministers, or Cabinet. The
Communists, who until this year had controlled the government since
1948, would have the ministries of interior, defense, transportation
and foreign trade.
   Government and legislative sources said more posts could be added.
   Late Friday, the parliamentary commission for food and
agriculture voted against the nominations of Czeslaw Janicki of the
Peasant Party and Artur Balazs of Solidarity, television news said.
   Janicki, an agriculture professor, was nominated for the combined
post of deputy prime minister and agriculture, and Balazs as
minister without portfolio for rural and civic issues. The TV report
said voting was secret and gave no reasons for the rejections.
   The new government will face an economy ravaged by inflation, a
chronic shortage of basic goods, low productivity and a foreign debt
of $39 billion.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
