<FIRST>r i PM-MotherTeresa     09-09 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother Teresa,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa's Condition Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa, the Roman Catholic nun
whose devotion to the destitute and dying earned her a Nobel Peace
Prize, remained in intensive care today recovering from a heart
attack, a co-worker said.
   ``There has been no change in her condition since yesterday
(Friday),'' said a nun at the Missionaries of Charity, the order
founded by Mother Teresa to care for the poor in this eastern Indian
city. She requested anonymity.
   Mother Teresa's doctors refused to answer questions about her
health, and hospital officials said a statement would be issued
later in the day.
   The frail 79-year-old nun suffered a heart attack Friday, three
days after she was admitted to Woodlands Hospital with a high fever
and irregular heartbeat. Doctors said her condition had stablized
and she was improving.
   She became ill on Sunday night but insisted on attending Mass on
Monday. Her condition continued to deteriorate, and on Tuesday she
hospitalized.
   The soft-spoken nun, who was born in Yugoslavia, has become known
for her work with the poor. She received dozens of honors, including
the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize and the U.S. Presidential Medal of
Freedom, which she received in 1985 from then-President Reagan.
   Despite heart problems and failing eyesight, Mother Teresa
continued to travel widely in recent years and spoke out vigorously
against abortion.
   She founded the Missionaries of Charity in October 1950 in an
abandoned, run-down hostel donated by the city. The order,
recognized by the Vatican in 1965, now has 3,000 nuns working in 87
countries.
</TEXT>
