<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees     09-09 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>70 East Germans Flee Over Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 70 East Germans, five Romanians and
a Bulgarian fled from Hungary to Austria overnight, seeking freedom
and a new life in the West, a Red Cross official said today.
   The number of East Germans making the risky overnight dash across
the border was down from the 100 or so who arrived early Friday.
   Red Cross officials attributed the drop to new hopes that more
than 6,000 East Germans now waiting in Hungary to go to West Germany
will be allowed to leave en masse in the next few days.
   Officials in Budapest said Friday they expect the thousands of
East German refugees to leave for the West within days from tent
camps, summer cabins and other makeshift lodgings where many have
spent weeks.
   Hungary has been caught between the two Germanys, anxious to
prove to Bonn that it is committed to human rights but worried about
angering the orthodox leadership in East Berlin. Negotiations were
under way to resolve the issue.
   Another 6,000 East Germans have fled to Austria from Hungary this
summer since Budapest began removing barbed wire and other barriers
from its border with Austria in May. All but one have gone on to
West Germany, where they receive automatic citizenship and help in
starting a new life.
   Few East Germans are allowed to visit the West, but trips to
neighboring Hungary have been easy to arrange.
   The Hungarian border increasingly is serving as a way West for
other Soviet bloc citizens who seek asylum in Austria, Red Cross
officials say.
   Most nights this week, Romanian citizens have been among those
arriving in Austria, which has a policy of caring for them while
they apply to become political refugees or seek emigration to
another Western nation.
   Today's new arrivals included five Romanians and one Bulgarian,
Red Cross officials said. Earlier this week, a Soviet citizen was
among those crossing from Hungary.
</TEXT>
