<HEAD>At Least 13 Hurt in Gas Leak Explosion In Dallas Apartment Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A natural gas explosion ripped through an apartment
complex, injuring at least 13 people, two critically, said fire
authorities who continued to search for more victims today.
   A leak or break in a gas line at the Robin Village Apartments
occurred Friday evening after maintenance workers attempted repairs
there, said a Dallas fire department spokesman.
   Fire Capt. Don Howard said 13 people were injured, including
several who had to be rescued from the debris. Rescuers were
checking the debris today to see if there was anyone still trapped.
   Four apartments were heavily damaged in the explosion, but there
was no fire damage because ``the explosion had such force that it
blew the fire out,'' Howard said.
   Apartment residents said they had smelled gas shortly before the
blast.
   Clifton Cleveland, a 44-year-old maintenance worker at the
complex, and Edward Robertson, 39, were in critical condition today
at Parkland Memorial Hospital with severe burns, said hospital
spokeswoman Becky Posell.
   Two children, ages 5 and 8, were hospitalized in fair condition,
two children and three adults were treated and released, and the
condition of the four other injured persons was not immediately
available.
   Howard said the exact cause of the blast had not been officially
determined but maintenance workers probably triggered it while
trying to repair the leak.
