<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     09-09 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Demand End to Beirut Battles</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of refugees from Christian-Syrian
fighting marched through the streets of Sidon today during
torrential rains to appeal for an end to the battles and a chance to
go home.
   ``Have mercy on us! We want to return to our city,'' they
shouted, their voices mingling with thunder claps.
   Three people were killed and 12 wounded in today's exchanges over
Beirut's Christian and Moslem neighborhoods, police said. Rockets,
artillery rounds and tank fire rained onto residential neighborhoods
near the battlefront.
   Making matters worse for refugees, heavy rain flooded fields and
river banks where thousands have been camping outside Beirut to
escape the battlezone. In Sidon, about 25 miles south of the
capital, 200 refugees took part in the unscheduled protest.
   A prominent city politician tried to calm the demonstrators.
Oussama Saad, a Sunni Moslem, told them they would be given shelter
at government schools.
   However, a protest organizer yelled back: ``We don't want
charity! We don't want shelter! We want our Beirut back!''
   The Christians and Syrians allied with local militia fighters
began their duels in March after the Christian leader, Gen. Michel
Aoun, blockaded militia ports in an effort to recover lost levies.
Aoun leads a Christian Cabinet challenging a Moslem-led government.
   About 40,000 Syrian troops moved into Lebanon under terms of a
1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. Aoun says they lost their
credibility as peacekeepers by siding with Moslem and leftist
factions, and he has vowed to drive them out of the country.
   The warring forces also fought today on a mountain ridge east of
the capital and a coastal highway to the north. No casualties were
reported from the fighting in those areas.
   Today's victims from the Beirut bloodshed raised the overall toll
to 833 killed and 2,474 wounded since the outbreak of fighting on
March 8.
   Most of Beirut's 1.5 million people have fled to safer areas or
left the country altogether in recent weeks as the fighting
escalated into some of the most destructive battles of the
14-year-old civil war.
   Only 150,000 people have remained in Beirut, police estimate.
They are generally trapped in underground shelters most of the time
and suffer from acute shortages of supplies.
   Thousands of Beirut refugees have been camping on the banks of
the Awali River, the northern entrance to Sidon. The overnight
downpour knocked down many of their tents and makeshift wooden
shacks. Rain is unusual for this time of year in Lebanon, where
winter starts in late October.
</TEXT>
