<FIRST>u i PM-Denmark-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru   09-09 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denmark-Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0484,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims of Plane Crash Were Taking Free Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to note that identification of aircraft model
has changed. Pickup 5th pvs, `All 50...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 55 people who died when a
charter plane crashed in the North Sea were lottery winners taking a
free trip to West Germany, the company that sponsored the contest
said.
   Forty ships and a helicopter today searched the waters off
Denmark's west coast for bodies from Friday's crash, Denmark's
public radio said.
   The twin-engine CV-580 Convair turboprop plane was traveling from
Oslo, Norway, to Hamburg, West Germany, when it went down 18 miles
north of the Danish fishing port of Hirtshals. The cause of the
crash was not known.
   Rescue officials previously had identified the aircraft as a
Convair 440, but company officials said it was a CV-580.
   All 50 passengers, employees of the Wilhelmsen Lines shipping
company of Oslo, and the crew of five were presumed dead. Three
women passengers carried British passports but were living in
Norway, the company said.
   A West German navy vessel taking part in a NATO sea exercise in
the area at the time of the crash pulled 31 bodies from the water
and brought them to Hirtshals where Danish officials began the task
of identification. Rescue officials said previously that 32 bodies
were recovered.
   The U.S.-built plane belonged to the Norwegian Partnair charter
airline company.
   In Oslo, the shipping company released the passenger list with
the names of 38 men and 17 women.
   The passengers, most of the top management and half of the staff
of Wilhelmsen Lines, were chosen by lottery for the trip to see a
ship christened in West Germany, company officials said.
   ``This is unbelievable tragedy on what was supposed to be a day
of celebration,'' said Leif Terje Loeddesoel, president of Wilh.
Wilhelmsen Ltd., the shipping line's parent company.
   Next of kin, many crying, arrived at the concern's Oslo office
late Friday and early today where a crisis team of pychologists and
clergymen awaited them.
   Clusters of people whose friends worked for the company gathered
outside its offices today waiting for a list of victims to be made
public.
   A Norwegian air disaster commission was preparing to go to
Hirtshals to work with Danish officials trying to determine the
cause of the crash.
   ``It would be pure speculation to say what caused the crash, but
whatever it was it must have happened very suddenly,'' said Rolf
Grimsrud, director of the Norwegian Civil Aviation technical
division.
   ``It could have been an explosion, due to sabotage or something
else, or it could have lost a major surface, such as a wing or the
tail,'' he said.
   Public radio quoted flight supervisor Karl Andersen at
Copenhagen's Kastrup Airport as saying that parts of the plane might
have broken off in mid-air.
   ``The radar signal disappeared very suddenly from our screens,
and it (the plane) went down fast,'' Andersen was quoted as saying.
   The Convair probably disintegrated when it hit the water, he
added.
   It was flying at an altitude of 23,000 feet when air controllers
at Kastrup Airport lost contact with it.
   Rescuers said most of the bodies were found within a radius of a
few hundred yards, which would appear to indicate that the plan did
not explode in mid-air.
   Partnair's managing director, Syvar Leivestad, said a fishing
boat picked up an underwater sonar echo that might be the wreckage,
but West German navy divers sent down to check could not confirm the
report due to poor visibility.
   The plane was built by General Dynamics 35 years ago and its
engines were refitted about 20 years ago.
   One week ago it had undergone a five-week maintenance check in
Canada before going back into service at Partnair.
   ``Despite being old our planes have less total mileage than many
planes built in the 1970s,'' Leivestad said.
</TEXT>
