<HEAD>United States Sends Envoy to Discuss Peace With Former Afghan King</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf bgng ``The king ... '' to CORRECT that Soviet-backed
coup took place in 1978.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration official says the United
States has sent a special envoy to the former King of Afghanistan to
discuss a possible political settlement of the Afghan civil war.
   The king, Zahir Shah, has been living in Rome since he was
deposed in 1973. A Soviet-backed coup took place in 1978, and a year
later Soviet forces invaded to install another puppet government.
   The Afghan government has faced a U.S.-supported insurgency that
was widely expected to topple the Soviet-supported government after
the withdrawal of Soviet troops in February.
   However, the government has held on, helped by both continuing
heavy arms shipments from the Soviet union and heavy air support as
well as disunity among the rebel factions.
   The United States has been exploring a political settlement for
several months.
   The king has both supporters and opponents among the resistance
groups.
   The U.S. envoy visited the king in Rome last week, said the
official who disclosed the visits Friday night, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   It was at least the second such consultation, he said. ``It was
not an extraordinary event.'' He declined to identify the envoy.
   In Rome, Gen. Abdul Wali, the king's brother-in-law and
spokesman, today declined to comment on the reported meeting.
   ``As a rule, we do not comment about these matters,'' he said.
``I really have no comment to make on this.''
