<FIRST>u i PM-India-SriLanka 2ndLd-Writethru   09-09 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0488,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Says it Will Withdraw Troops By Year's End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with India withdrawing troops before
year's end. Pickup 4th pvs, `Sri Lanka's...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India will withdraw its peacekeeping
troops from Sri Lanka on or before Dec. 31, a senior government
official said today.
   An agreement on the new withdrawal date was reached by Indian and
Sri Lankan officials during a meeting of non-aligned nations in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, the official said. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi said Friday in New Delhi that
an agreement had been reached on the pullout of the estimated 42,000
Indian soldiers from Sri Lanka's northeast. But he refused to give
details.
   Gandhi held at least two meeting in Belgrade with Sri Lankan
Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne, who led his country's delegaion
at the non-algined meeting. Wijeratne also met with his Indian
counterpart, P.V. Narasimha Rao.
   The Sri Lankan official said Wijeratne told President Ranasinghe
Premadasa of the Indian proposal to withdraw Indian troops on or
before Dec. 31.
   Also today, the Sri Lankan government said in a statement that
Premadasa has agreed to examine opposition demands for reforms that
would overhaul the structure of the government.
   ``All these proposals need careful study and examination with a
view to achieving peace, normalcy and stability,'' the government
statement quoted Premadasa as telling the leaders of five opposition
parties on Friday night.
   Sri Lanka's opposition is calling for the formation of a
provisional government, the replacement of the presidential system
of government by the earlier parliamentary system, new elections and
efforts to bring anti-government militants to the democratic
mainstream.
   Opposition leaders met with Premadasa before an all-party
conference that he will convene on Wednesday.
   As Premasada met with opposition leaders, security forces killed
eight Sinhalese radicals in a continuing crackdown in central and
southern Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese heartland, the government said.
   Five militants were killed in a police attack in Peradeniya town
in Kandy district, 55 miles northeast of Colombo, a communique said.
Three radicals died in an ambush by soldiers in Kalutara district,
25 miles south of Colombo, the communique said. No other details
were disclosed.
   Elsewhere, a Sinhalese police constable and a woman were shot to
death by extremists in southern Sri Lanka and more than 235
suspected Sinhalese militants were arrested, the communique said.
   Sinhalese radicals belonging to the People's Liberation Front
have been trying for more than two years to overthrow the
Sinhalese-dominated government.
   They claim the government granted too many concessions to the
minority Tamils demanding a separate homeland in north and east Sri
Lanka and compromised the country's sovereignty by inviting India to
send its peacekeeping troops to help end the Tamil rebellion.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of the island's 16 million people.
They claim they are denied jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and
military.
   India, the regional power and home of more than 60 million
Tamils, mediated the July 1987 peace accord that offered the Tamils
limited autonomy if they surrendered their weapons.
   The accord was rejected by the largest and most militant Tamil
group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, which began fighting
Indian forces.
   Premadasa earlier demanded Indian troops leave the island once
known as Ceylon by July 29, the second anniversary of the peace
accord. But Gandhi refused, saying a hasty withdrawal could lead to
even more bloodshed.
   The presence of Indian soldiers became a point of contention
between the two countries and resulted in a diplomatic deadlock that
at one point threatened to snowball into an armed confrontation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
