<FIRST>r i PM-ConsulateRansacked 1stLd-Writethru a0492 09-09 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consulate Ransacked, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Ransack South Africa's Consulate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adds 2 grafs of background on squatters. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked activists stormed South
Africa's Consulate in Copenhagen and extensively damaged the offices
by throwing acid and setting small fires, newspaper reports said
today.
   Late Friday 20 to 30 people arrived in front of the consulate in
a truck, jumped out and smashed down the doors of the building with
wooden rams and crowbars, the Copenhagen newspaper Berlingske
Tidende reported.
   The masked intruders then vandalized the consulate offices by
pouring acid on the floor, smashing inventory, and scattering and
burning papers, the newspaper said.
   Police in riot gear arrived on the scene within a few minutes of
the break-in but failed to arrest any of the activists who had
strewn the street with steel blades to puncture the tires of the
police vans.
   Police said the activists were members of a squatter movement
known as BZ which has been in numerous violent confrontations with
the authorities in recent years, the paper said.
   It said the action was an apparent protest against this week's
South African elections in which the black majority was not allowed
to vote.
   The squatter movement is made up of several groups of youths who
have illegally occupied derelict buildings in Copenhagen for years.
Police have failed to evict them despite using force.
   BZ also is believed to have been behind a series of attacks on
Shell gas stations, presumably to protest Shell's business ties in
South Africa.
</TEXT>
