<HEAD>Broadcast Workers Strike in South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 workers at one of the
country's two national broadcasting networks went on strike for the
second day Saturday, forcing regular radio and television programs
to be curtailed.
   The strikers say they want a say in selecting department chiefs
to ensure fairness and protect the company from government
interference. They say past authoritarian governments have tampered
with editorial policy.
   A union spokesman at Moonhwa Broadcasting Co. said the strike
will continue until its demands are met.
   Company officials said newscasters were replaced with non-union
members. They said some live programs, such as news and talk shows,
were suspended or shortened.
   The Korea Broadcasting System is the larger of the two national
broadcasting networks in South Korea.
