<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0434 09-09 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forcing Down Drug-Running Planes Urged in Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf bgng ``I agree with ... '' to CORRECT that Bennett
was testifying before Foreign Relations Committee, sted Judiciary.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators are calling for use of force as a last
resort to down planes delivering cocaine, and national drug policy
director William Bennett isn't ruling out such a policy.
   ``I agree with the sentiment expressed, Senator,'' Bennett said
Friday after Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and other lawmakers urged
such action at a Senate Foreign Relations Committee session.
   Bennett stopped short of endorsing a McConnell amendment that
would provide law enforcement officials with such powers, but
acknowledged that the concept had appeal.
   ``It is analogous to, not identical to, but analogous to, it
seems to me, the authority we give a police officer in the inner
city in this country to stop someone from speeding away in a four by
four,'' Bennett said.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., told the panel that if a drug-running
plane was ordered to land and refused to do so, then as a last
resort, ``I think we should blow it out of the air.''
   At the hearing, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., questioned Bennett
about reports that there have been cutbacks in a Miami-based program
designed to ferret out money-laundering drug kingpins, ``Operation
Greenback.''
   Bennett said he was unaware of it, but an aide, Bruce Karnes,
said, ``I have heard of it.'' He said after the hearings that he had
no details.
   ``Apparently there have been some cutbacks,'' said John Hanlon, a
spokesman for the Internal Revenue Service, which has been operating
the program in conjunction with the Justice Department. He said
details would not be available immediately.
   Bennett said there was no plan to send U.S. fighting troops to
Colombia to engage the cocaine cartel. Among other things, he said,
Colombian President Virgilio Barco does not want foreign troops in
his country.
   The same applied to any multinational military force designed to
fight the drug lords, Bennett added.
   He said that if Colombia asked for troops to combat the cartel,
the United States would have to consider the request, but he added
that the possibility seemed remote and that there are no plans on
the drawing board.
   He said American officials aim to keep the several hundred U.S.
military advisers in Colombia away from any hostilities, but added
that there could be no guarantee.
   ``Hostilities can break out anyplace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
