<HEAD>Bomb Goes off at Village Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERESSOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded on a beach at this popular
tourist village on the eastern Aegean island of Lesbos Saturday but
caused no injuries, police said.
   Antenna, an Athens commercial radio station, said an anonymous
caller who warned about the bomb claimed to represent a previously
unknown group, the Patriotic Liberation Front of 1989.
   A policeman in Eressos would not confirm that report, and it was
not clear exactly what political motive such a group would have had.
   The blast occurred far from shops and camping sites in the early
afternoon after two warning calls to the police station, Eressos
police said.
   The beach was evacuated, and there were no injuries, said a
spokesman on condition of anonmity.
   He gave no details on what type of device exploded.
