<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 3rdLd-Writethru   09-09 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0503,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Baron Freed, Members of Death Squad Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to RAISE HIGHER U.S. comment on freed trafficker.
Pickup 2nd pvs, ``The army...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking drug trafficker imprisoned
for the past month at the height of the drug crackdown was released
because authorities lacked an extradition request from the United
States, police said.
   However, a Drug Enforcement Administration official in Washington
said the trafficker was not being sought in the United States.
   The army said today it captured the four leading members of a
cocaine death squad in the drug center of Medellin and said the men
also served as bodyguards for the wife of fugitive drug kingpin
Pablo Escobar.
   Botoga's El Tiempo newspaper said today the army raided 30 sites
in Bogota and the rural town of Pacho and seized 49 vehicles,
including two bulletproof Mercedez Benz sedans, thought to belong to
drug boss Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha.
   In other developments:
   _The army said Friday it had arrested the pilot of one of the
nation's top cocaine barons and that he had flown cocaine to the
United States.
   _In Medellin armed gangs wearing white hoods terrorized the
embattled city Friday, setting fire to nine government vehicles,
including trucks and vans. The gangs, suspected of working for the
drug lords, hurled firebombs and fired shots in the air. No injuries
were reported, and police arrested one man. Many businesses closed
after receiving death threats over the telephone.
   Regarding the trafficker who was freed, police identified him as
a key aide to Escobar and said he was released Thursday because
there was no arrest warrant, legal paperwork, or extradition request
for him by the United States.
   Police Col. Oscar Pelaez Carmona said the aide, Luis Fernando
Galeano, was held at an army base for a month after being arrested
during a raid on a Medellin office building believed to house money
laundering operations. Pelaez said Galeano also was arrested in 1988
on charges of money laundering but had to be released because all
the legal paperwork on him disappeared.
   It was not known why his latest arrest was not made public either
in Colombia or the United States, which is helping Colombia with
financial aid and military equipment in its war on drugs and seeking
the extradition of top drug lords. The government began the
crackdown last month after a police chief, a judge and a
presidential candidate were killed in attacks blamed on dealers.
   Escobar, who leads the United States' most-wanted list, is said
to head a $3 billion worldwide cocaine empire. The government of
Colombia has offered a $250,000 reward for information leading to
his arrest.
   Colombian newspapers have said Galeano is a financial
administrator for the Medellin cartel and have linked him to the
assassination of city councilman in the town of Monteria and the
attempted slaying of a man connected to a rival drug cartel in the
city of Cali.
   In Washington, Frank Shultz, a spokesman for the federal Drug
Enforcement Administration, said Galeano was not wanted in the
United States and that there were no charges against him.
   Regarding the arrest of the death squad members, the 4th Army
Brigade in Medellin said in a communique that the gang, called
``Love for Medellin,'' took its name from a local charitable
organization and operated as a vigilante gang that killed suspected
drug addicts, prostitutes and homosexuals.
   It did not say when the four men were captured, but it said
``Love for Medellin'' frequently guarded Maria Victoria Henao
Vallejo, the wife of Escobar, alleged head of the Medellin cocaine
cartel.
   The newspaper El Tiempo said it received its information about
the confiscation of the drug barons' property from military sources.
   The Defense Department's press office was closed for the weekend.
   Colombian military authorities earlier showed reporters documents
attesting to vast holdings of Rodriguez Gacha, in which the reputed
drug boss, now in hiding, operated like a one-man multinational
corporation.
   The government, using its emergency powers, this week assigned a
military officer to replace the elected mayor of Pacho, 50 miles
northwest of Bogota. But it rescinded the action a few hours later,
after political parties said the move was unconstitutional.
   The army announced Friday it had arrested Escobar's pilot,
Nicolas Gonzalez Cardona, who allegedly flew cocaine to the United
States. The pilot was arrested in raids in the opening days of the
crackdown.
   The army said in a communique that Gonzalez made ``international
flights on one of the Medellin cartel's main routes'' between
Colombia, Miami and New York. The cartel is believed to supply 80
percent of the U.S. cocaine supply.
</TEXT>
