<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Catastrophic     09-09 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Topsy-Turvy: Deficit Helping Save Major Social Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one of the ironic twists that could happen
only in Washington, it appears the federal budget deficit is all
that is standing in the way of killing a major social program _
catastrophic health insurance for retirees.
   The way the government works, repealing the program would worsen
next year's deficit by about $5 billion. That's because taxes to
finance catastrophic are being collected more quickly then benefits
are being paid.
   Some who watch Congress closely say that even the deficit problem
is not enough to save the new insurance program. They predict the
House and Senate will repeal it.
   Catastrophic, which everyone eligible for Medicare is required to
buy, is under attack from some retirees who already have such
coverage and from some wealthier older Americans who don't like
having to buy coverage for those with lower incomes.
   Because of a barrage of complaints, the House Ways and Means
Committee and the Senate Finance Committee are making major changes
in the program, reducing benefits and cutting the surtax on
higher-income retirees that provides most of the money. But in Ways
and Means especially, there is heavy sentiment for repeal.
   Will the changes be enough to stave off repeal? Senate Majority
Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, was asked.
   ``I don't know that,'' replied Mitchell, a member of the Finance
Committee.
   When Senate Republican leaders met with President Bush at the
White House last week, they came down hard for repeal. The
administration wants no changes.
   Neither committee will advocate repeal, because if it did so, it
would have to find about $5 billion of new taxes to prevent
worsening of the deficit.
   However, when the hotly disputed issue reaches the floor of the
House, congressional aides predict, most lawmakers will be unable to
resist voting for repeal.
   When the catastrophic-coverage law was enacted a year ago,
Congress and the Reagan administration agreed that it should be set
up like an insurance program. At least in the early years, money to
finance benefits would be collected at a faster pace than benefits
would be paid out.
   The first part of coverage went into effect this year, providing
some protection against expenses of a lengthy hospital stay.
Doctors' bills will be covered starting next year; most prescription
drugs will be covered starting in 1991.
   Some of the taxes and fees that finance catastrophic benefits are
already being paid by retirees; the biggest part of the bill will
become due when tax returns are filed early in 1990. But for at
least most of 1990, significantly less will be going out in benefit
checks than is being paid in.
   The Office of Management and Budget estimates that if
catastrophic coverage were repealed, the 1990 deficit would be
swollen by between $4 billion and $7 billion. That would be enough
under the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law to trigger automatic
reductions in most federal programs.
   But what is happening to those taxes and fees that retirees are
paying for catastrophic coverage? The money is being mixed with all
other tax dollars in the treasury _ paying federal salaries, buying
weapons and fighting illegal drugs.
   The money also is making the budget deficit look smaller than it
is _ and that's another burr under the saddle of those who don't
like the catastrophic program.
   When OMB Deputy Director William Diefenderfer was asked about
repeal at a Finance Committee session last week, he replied, ``Any
model I've seen for repeal increases the deficit. Therefore, we
would have to oppose it.''
   ``Does this program make money?'' demanded Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y. ``Is that why you want it?''
   Diefenderfer hastened to add that Bush likes the program for what
it does for retirees.
   But opponents of catastrophic coverage had another argument for
repeal. Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., accused the administration of
favoring the program as part of a strategy to balance the budget
``from the already-inadequate pensions of America's seniors.''
</TEXT>
