<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-09 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Nominees Outline Dramatic New Policies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabinet nominees to the Solidarity-led
government on Saturday unveiled plans for a Western-style tax system
and a liberalized economy, saying radical changes are crucial to
removing the vestiges of Communist control.
   The proposals were outlined for members of Parliament, who will
have final say on the new government proposed by Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   The 24-member Council or Ministers, or Cabinet, would include 12
ministers clearly aligned with the Solidarity labor movement. The
Communists would get four posts, although they have been guaranteed
control of the key defense and interior ministries.
   The shape of Poland's historic new government began to emerge as
Parliament members quizzed Cabinet nominees on economic, political
and social issues.
   ``We face an economic process unknown in history. Nobody ever
tried to pass from the socialist economy to a free-market economy,''
said Witold Trzeciakowski, a Solidarity adviser nominated as
chairman of the Economic Advisory Council.
   Solidarity's Leszek Balcerowicz, nominated as vice premier and
finance minister, outlined an overhaul in the tax system that
includes lowering taxes on profits and instituting a progressive
personal income tax and a value-added tax, a form of sales tax.
   Controls on wage inflation, liberalizing foreign trade rules,
protecting the drain of goods and capital from Poland and unifying
the official and black-market currency exchange rates also will be
part of the program, he said.
   The Parliament committees, which began the hearings Friday, have
generally given favorable assessments.
   The committee assessments are advisory, and the final decision
will be up to the Sejm, the powerful lower house of parliament which
is to vote on the cabinet Tuesday. A Solidarity-led coalition
controls the chamber, and it is unclear how it will react to
Mazowiecki's nominees, who are considered compromise candidates to
placate the Communists.
   By heading the interior and defense ministries, the Communists
will retain control of the army and police, although it remains
unclear how much power Mazowiecki will have to overrule individual
ministries.
   ``The army is a pro-reform institution,'' Gen. Florian Siwicki, a
Communist nominated to remain defense minister, declared to one
committee Saturday.
   Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, Mazowiecki's predecessor as prime minister
and his nominee to remain head of the Interior Ministry, told a
committee he will not nominate non-Communists as his deputies.
   He said that would invite ``political discussions'' making it
difficult to execute his powers, but he added that he wants the
ministry independent of party control and he will be loyal to
Mazowiecki.
   Also joining Mazowiecki's proposed government are the Peasant
Party and Democratic Party, former Communist Party allies who
shifted allegiance to Solidarity and creating a coalition strong
enough to convince the Communists to cede control.
   Peasant Party members have been nominated to four posts and
Democrats to three.
   The foreign minister nominee, lawyer Krzysztof Skubiszewski, is
considered an independent, although he is friendly toward Solidarity.
   Skubiszewski said he would like his foreign ministry ``to open a
very difficult matter'' amd make possible the return of deported
Poles forced to remain in the Soviet Union after World War II.
   Jacek Kuron, a veteran opposition activist nominated as labor
minister, said the law on strikes would be amended to simplify the
procedure for staging a legal work stoppage, while introducing the
principle that no wages are paid to strikers.
   Because of the disparate and still-evolving elements in Poland's
embryonic government, officials have cautioned that compromises and
debates in the coming days still could alter the makeup of the
government that Mazowiecki has proposed.
   Despite the Western slant the new government may take, the
Communist Party will still wield considerable economic power through
President Wojciech Jaruzelski, who appointed Politburo member
Wladyslaw Baka as president of the National Bank of Poland,
newspapers reported Saturday.
   But the Communists will no longer control the vast minsterial
bureaucracies they have run since 1948. Mazowiecki has promised
personnel decisions based on competence, not a ``witch hunt.''
   Solidarity Leader Lech Walesa, who put together the coalition
that elected Mazowiecki, was maintaining a distance from the
historic changes in keeping with his role as opposition figure. He
said he will not be pulling the strings from behind the scenes.
   ``No, I am out,'' he told the state news agency PAP. ``I am
interested only in pluralism, freedom and democracy. And when
everything works, I am really going on vacation. I will not enter
the government.''
</TEXT>
