<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     09-09 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Appeal for End to Beirut Battles</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 refugees from Beirut fighting,
shouting ``Have mercy on us,'' protested in Sidon Saturday to demand
a halt to six months of battles between Christian and Syrian forces.
   Police said military duels Saturday in the capital area killed
three people and wounded 12. The latest casualties raised the toll
to 833 people killed and 2,474 wounded since the fighting broke out
in March.
   As the refugees marched in Sidon, they chanted, ``Have mercy on
us, we want to return to our city!''
   Ousama Saad, an official of the Popular Nasserite militia that
controls Sidon, told demonstrators they will be sheltered in
government-run schools during the weekend.
   ``We don't want charity! We don't want shelters! We want our
Beirut back!'' a demonstrator shouted back.
   Schools have been closed throughout Lebanon during the
confrontation between Michel Aoun's mostly Christian forces and
Syrians allied with local militias. The fighting broke out after
Aoun blockaded ports run illegally by the militias.
   Aoun has vowed to drive out the 40,000 Syrian troops, who came to
Lebanon under terms of a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. He
says they have sided with the Moslems in the country's 14-year-old
civil war.
   In Beirut, about 20 members of the International Youth for Peace
Movement gathered Saturday for about 15 minutes at a
Moslem-Christian crossing to demand an end to fighting. They
released six white pigeons to symbolize peace.
   The group, which included several foreigners, broke up as the
crackle of machine guns echoed nearby.
   Unusually heavy rains and high winds struck Lebanon on Friday,
uprooting tents and some flimsy shacks that had sheltered the
refugees on the outskirts of Sidon.
   About 300 families, mainly Sunni Moslems from Beirut, have been
camping on the banks of the Awali River at the southern provincial
capital of Sidon about 25 miles from Beirut.
   ``May Allah's wrath fall on all the combatants. Their dirty war
has destroyed our houses and prevented us from repairing them,''
said Aisha Itani, a housewife. She has been living in a tent on the
river bank with her husband and two sons.
   According to police estimates, all but 150,000 of Beirut's 1.5
million people have fled the city for safer areas during the
fighting. Many of the refugees have been living in tents, cars and
shacks in fields and on river banks awaiting an end to the fighting.
   Also Saturday, rival Christian and Moslem leaders urged a
three-member Arab League mediation committee to resume its stalled
peace efforts.
   The committee _ which includes leaders of Saudi Arabia, Morocco
and Algeria _ said July 28 it was suspending its efforts on Lebanon
and blamed Syria for blocking its mission.
   The committee is to hold a meeting in the Saudi Red Sea port of
Jeddah Wednesday to decide if it can take up its mission again.
   Sunni Moslem leader Sheik Mohammed Rashid Kabbani, in a statement
broadcast by the Moslem Voice of the Nation radio, said he
``welcomes the revival of Arab efforts to deal with the Lebanese
crisis.''
   A Christian Cabinet led by Aoun, which is vying for power with
the Syrian-backed Moslem government of Salim Hoss, also welcomed the
committee's efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
