<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   09-09 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0483,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Proposes Soviet-Free Military Accord With Austria, Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to include Nyers saying Austria and Yugoslavia
told about proposal. Pickup 4th pvs, `The reformist.. .'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary is seeking a military accord
with Yugoslavia and Austria, the first time a Warsaw Pact nation has
sought to forge such an agreement with nations that do not belong to
the Soviet-led alliance.
   Communist Party chief Rezsoe Nyers unveiled the proposal Friday
that includes creation of a security zone with the two neighbors
that would be free of Warsaw Pact tanks.
   Nyers also said he would remove 14 of the 28 nuclear launching
pads in Hungary to reduce military costs and improve relations with
the West.
   The proposal awaits formal government adoption before being
presented to Austria and Yugoslavia, but he and other Communist
leaders consulted with the two neighboring countries before
presenting it Friday, Nyers said.
   ``We consulted with Vienna and Belgrade and received favorable
feedback,'' he said during a news conference in the capital.
   The reformist leader said he would ask the Soviet Union to pull
out two armored battalions, 72 tanks, from a planned security zone
that Hungary envisions establishing with neutral Austria and
non-aligned Yugoslavia.
   The initiative illustrates the great changes in the Soviet bloc
since Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev took power in 1985.
   As a member of the Warsaw Pact alliance, Hungary normally acts in
concert with its six military allies. Nyers said Moscow had been
consulted on parts of the plan that directly involve the Soviet
Union, but neighboring Czechoslovakia and Romania, which also are
allied, were not.
   ``The present foreign policy doctrine of the Warsaw Pact allows
for independent initiatives by member countries,'' he told
reporters. Nyers was apparently alluding to a Warsaw Pact meeting in
July that ended with the seven member nations pledging to let each
go their own way.
   Hungary plans multiparty elections by June, the first since it
became a Communist country. The nation is at odds with the rigid
Communist leadership of Romania and Czechoslovakia over political,
ecologial and human rights issues.
   Its plan to unilaterally improve military ties with its
non-Warsaw Pact neighbors was likely to worsen tensions with those
Communist allies.
   Nyers' proposal includes:
   _Halving the number of launching pads capable of delivering
nuclear devices.
   _Calling on the Soviet Union to withdraw two armored battalions
from a 35-mile buffer zone along common borders with Austria and
Yugoslavia and scrapping 200 Hungarian tanks now in the zone.
   _Asking Austria and Yugoslavia to declare security zones on their
sides of the border, expanding the common buffer zone to 60 miles.
   _Providing information on the size and location of forces within
the zone.
   _Limiting the frequency and size of military maneuvers and
allowing military observers from the two neighboring countries to
attend such exercises.
   Nyers also proposes that the three countries join forces to limit
and reduce military-related nuclear activities, to ban chemical
weapons, and to explore jointly cutting military expenditures.
   Nyers offered no further details about the location of the
nuclear launch bases or the range of missiles they could be used for.
   Hungary in May removed its border fortications with Austria,
allowing thousands of East bloc residents to flee to the West.
Hungary, like Poland, is embarking on a wide range of liberal
economic and political reforms and is seeking closer ties to the
West to bolster its economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
