<DOCNO> AP890909-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PublicRadio-Sports     09-09 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Radio-Sports,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>NPR Betting That Odds Are With New Sports Format</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cate in 8th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Public Radio is taking a new hard line
on sports.
   If sports news is important, it gets on the air; if it isn't, it
doesn't.
   Pete Rose's gambling woes were important at NPR, as were the
death of Major League Baseball Commissioner Bart Giamatti and firing
of Dallas Cowboys football caoch Tom Landry.
   Until recently, NPR's popular ``Morning Edition'' show may have
tossed such stories into short, hourly compilations of scores and
games results that often are called the ``ghetto'' approach to radio
sports coverage.
   Not now.
   ``Sports today is no longer scores,'' says Robert Ferrante,
executive producer of ``Morning Edition,'' which has dropped its
hourly sports updates and now lets sports compete for airtime with
other types of news.
   NPR, a nonprofit, private corporation that provides national
programming and support for 377 stations nationwide, is touting its
``different kind of news'' in its first multimedia campaign for
``Morning Edition'' and ``All Things Considered.''
   Local TV stations are playing sprightly animated ads for the
shows, and national and regional magazines are scheduled to carry
print ads as part of a drive to expand the audience of 6 million who
are attracted to NPR news shows, NPR spokeswoman Cate Cowan said.
   The 10-year-old ``Morning Edition'' is an eclectic mix of
in-depth news, arts, business, political and science features and
interviews hosted by Bob Edwards. It still has segments by veteran
sportscasters Red Barber and Bill Littlefield, but it no longer
locks sports into hourly 3}-minute slots.
   ``It was too restrictive. It didn't give due attention to sports
as part of the culture of this country,'' Ferrante said in an
interview last week.
   The allegations that Rose, baseball's alltime hit leader and
manager of the Cincinnati Reds, bet on the game ``was a morality
play for America,'' Ferrante said.
   Giamatti's unexpected death a week after he barred Rose from
baseball ``is probably as important to a larger section of America
as any national leader,'' Ferrante added.
   ``The part that sports plays in our culture is a news story and
should be judged the same way as other news stories,'' Ferrante
added. ``Sports is news, sports is fitness, sports is health. Sports
today rarely reflect the outcome of the game.''
   Ferrante said scores now are delivered once on ``Morning
Edition'' ``as a quick measurement'' of sports activity. But he
denied that NPR was rolling back it's sports coverage.
   The features by Barber and Littlefield still air in the old
sports time slot and still are among the most popular features on
``Morning Edition,'' Ferrante said. The other sports carried
throughout the broadcast means more airtime for sports, he said.
   ``Since June 19 there have been 120 (sports) stories on `Morning
Edition,''' he said.
   The change appears to have been well received at public stations.
   ``I think it's a good idea to treat sports news as news when it
is news, rather than ghetto-ize it,'' said Iris Adler, news director
of public station WBUR-FM in Boston. ``Our listeners tune in for
news and information. I don't think they listen to us for one type
of news or feature story. All they want is quality.''
   ``I'm happy with the change,'' said Carol Pierson, program
director for all news station KQED-FM in San Francisco. ``I think
it's more logical to treat topics according to their news importance
rather than dedicating a specific amount of time to a particular
topic.''
   Pierson said a lot of public stations previously cut out the
hourly NPR sports segment to broadcast local news or sports, ``and
we were one of them. So I'd say sports is now getting on our air
more than it was before.''
   She noted NPR's new approach was more in line with sports
coverage on the major TV networks.
   ``You hear sports news if it is important, and none if it
isn't,'' she said.
   The change was not without its critics. Edwards, the affable host
of ``Morning Edition,'' thinks it was a bad idea, although he
admitted his probably was a minority view at NPR.
   He said listeners don't know when to tune in for the sports.
   Edwards said a recent Gallup Poll conducted for NPR mostly on
``Morning Edition,'' ``showed our listeners don't care much for
sports,'' so sports news should be placed where those who are
interested can find it.
   ``Sports fans expect to hear sports where they've always heard
sports. And people who don't like sports feel the rest of the news
is being trivialized by having sports in that slot,'' he said.
   Edwards said listeners ``sort of plan their activities'' around
certain segments of the show: ```Oh, that's Afghanistan. I can
shower now.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
