<FIRST>r a AM-People     09-09 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Screenwriter Barry Morrow, who won an
Academy Award for the script of ``Rain Man,'' has finally been
awarded his bachelor of arts degree by St. Olaf College.
   St. Olaf President Melvin George described Friday's presentation
as ``a production 20 years in the making.''
   Morrow thought he had earned the degree in 1970, when he first
attended the school's commencement, joining his classmates in the
procession to the podium to receive diplomas. But when he returned
to his seat and opened his diploma, he found a message: ``See Miss
Frayseth.''
   Morrow had spent his junior year studying in Hawaii. Miss
Frayseth, a St. Olaf registrar, had decided to reject certain
credits from Hawaii, leaving Morrow one credit short of graduation.
   After Morrow won an Oscar this year for best original screenplay
for ``Rain Man,'' college officials told him he could earn that
elusive final credit by handing in his script as a sort of
graduation thesis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State District Judge Catherine Crier, a former
actress and model, has resigned to become an anchorwoman for Cable
News Network, officials from the governor's office and the
Atlanta-based network said.
   ``We are most excited about taking someone from the bench to the
news desk,'' CNN spokesman Steve Haworth told The Dallas Morning
News.
   Ms. Crier, 34, has no experience in television journalism, but
Haworth said she ``has perfected the kinds of skills that a reporter
has to perfect.''
   Ms. Crier, who was elected to the bench in Dallas as a Republican
in 1984, will step down Sept. 30.
   As a college student, Ms. Crier was voted one of the 10 most
beautiful women at the University of Texas by actor Ryan O'Neal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of country music stars has
scheduled a concert Sept. 27 to benefit relief efforts for the
Alaska oil spill.
   Rodney Crowell, New Grass Revival, Russell Smith, Guy Clark, J.C.
Crowley and Hobo Jim are among artists scheduled to perform.
   Smith, who is spearheading the concert, said the proceeds will be
sent to the Prince William Sound Cleanup and Rehabilitation Fund
administered by the Alaska Conservation Foundation.
   Smith played benefit concerts in Alaska in June.
</TEXT>
