<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Bomber     09-09 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bomber,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Bomber To Be Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain said Saturday it will free an Iranian
convicted on bombing charges after nine years in prison. Iran has
indicated it would like to exchange the Iranian for a jailed Briton.
   The Foreign Office said it will release Kourosh Fouladi, a former
doorman at the Iranian Embassy who was convicted in 1982 after a car
bombing attempt and sentenced to 10 years in jail. Authorities said
two of Fouladi's accomplices were killed in the explosion in West
London.
   In August, Deputy Foreign Minister Mahmoud Vaezi of Iran linked
Fouladi's case with that of Roger Cooper, a Briton who has been
imprisoned in Iran without trial since 1985 on suspicion of spying.
   However, Foreign Office Minister William Waldegrave said earlier
this year there was no provision in British law for exchanging
Fouladi for Cooper.
   A British Foreign Office official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the Iranian's release ``has absolutely nothing to
do'' with Cooper.
   A spokesman for the Home Office, speaking about Fouladi's
release, said Saturday: ``He was convicted and sentenced to 10 years
which he has now served, taking into account normal remission which
is available to any prisoner. He will now be deported to Iran.''
   Britain had been trying to improve ties with Iran, but relations
soured after the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued a death
threat in February against British author Salman Rushdie.
</TEXT>
