<FIRST>r i AM-MotherTeresa     09-09 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Develops High Fever; Irregular Heartbeat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa developed a
high fever and an irregular heartbeat Saturday a day after suffering
a heart attack, hospital officials said.
   Doctors said they have decided to place a temporary pacemaker to
help the ailing heart of the frail 79-year-old nun, who has
dedicated her life to the destitute and dying.
   Officials at Woodlands Nursing Home, where Mother Teresa was
admitted Tuesday, refused to elaborate or say whether they already
implanted the pacemaker. In a statement, they said the nun is not
responding to medication.
   ``Her rising temperature and irregularity of pulse is causing
anxiety,'' the statement said.
   Mother Teresa became ill Sept. 3 and was admitted to the
hospital's intensive care unit last Tuesday. She suffered a heart
attack on Friday, but doctors had said her condition had stabilized
and she was improving.
   Saturday's statement said Mother Teresa spent a ``sleepless
night'' Friday but rested throughout the day Saturday.
   It said a renowned Calcutta physician had been called for
consultations, but did not name him. Mother Teresa's cardiologist in
Rome also has been contacted and may fly to Calcutta soon, the
statement said.
   Mother Teresa was born in Yugoslavia and received several honors
for her work with the poor in this eastern Indian city, including
the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize and the U.S. Presidential Medal of
Freedom, the highest American civilian award, which former President
Reagan presented to her in 1985.
   In October 1950, Mother Teresa founded the Missionaries of
Charity in an abandoned, run down hostel donated by city officials.
The order, recognized by the Vatican in 1965, now has 3,000 nuns
working in 87 countries.
   Despite heart problems and failing eyesight in recent years,
Mother Teresa traveled widely and vigorously spoke out against
abortion, an act she called ``the greatest sin a woman can commit.''
</TEXT>
