<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     09-09 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Condemn Shooting of Children; Violence Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors in Cape Town said they
have treated children as young as four years old with gunshot
wounds, which relatives said were inflicted by police during
election violence.
   Police said Saturday they used pistols, birdshot, rubber bullets
and tear gas to disperse mobs overnight and Saturday morning in
mixed-race townships near Cape Town, where violence has been
reported since Wednesday's elections. The elections excluded South
Africa's 28 million black majority.
   Also Saturday, the National Union of Mineworkers said three black
mineworkers were shot to death by private security guards in a
protest related to the elections. Mine owners said the workers
attacked the guards.
   ``It is extremely saddening to find children caught up in the
firing line,'' said Dr. David Bass, head of the Red Cross Children's
Hospital Trauma Unit. He said 10 children, aged four to 12, had been
treated there for birdshot or buckshot wounds on election day.
   Bass was one of 75 Cape Town area doctors who issued a statement
late Friday describing the injuries to children as ``barbaric and
stomach-turning.''
   Police issue daily unrest reports, which give few details, but
their extensive listing of more than 300 incidents from Wednesday
through Friday do not refer to any children being hurt by police
action.
   ``To apportion blame without being there is very difficult, but
to have buckshot and birdshot fired into crowds where there were
women and children present points to questionable responsibility,''
Bass said.
   Relatives of injured children have alleged that police shot them.
   He described some of his patients in an interview with the
independent South African Press Association.
   ``One of them, a four-year-old girl, has birdshot inside her
skull. Another eight-year-old girl has an eye injury and wounds to
her limbs and trunk. A 12-year-old boy was shot in the leg, foot and
buttocks,'' said Bass.
   The Ministry of Law and Order has disputed the claims of
anti-apartheid activists, clerics, doctors, journalists and township
residents who have reported indiscriminate police firing in the Cape
Town area during elections for parliamentary seats reserved for
whites, mixed-race and Asians. Blacks have no voice in national
affairs.
   Cape Town attorney Essa Moosa said Friday that 29 people were
killed on election night. He was referring to reports from
mortuaries, doctors, relatives and an ambulanceman.
   Most were killed by police, Moosa said, but some were involved in
factional fighting which he and other activists said was instigated
by police.
   Police have not acknowledged killing anyone, although they say 15
people died and 26 policemen were injured. They have reported only a
handful of civilian injuries from police shootings on election day,
while Cape Town activists and doctors have reported up to 200.
   On Saturday, police said in a statement that they fired pistols,
birdshot, rubber bullets and tear gas to disperse stone-throwers who
damaged vehicles in four mixed-race townships overnight and Saturday
morning. Pistols with live ammunition sometimes are used to fire
warning shots.
   ``No injuries were reported as a result of police action'' since
Wednesday, said the statement.
   One mixed-race man was hurt in a stoning incident, and four were
arrested for stoning a delivery vehicle, the statement said.
   In Johannesburg, meanwhile, the General Mining Union Corp. said
three people were killed and 11 injured Friday night when a crowd
armed with sharpened sticks and knives attacked security guards at a
workers hostel at Kinross gold mine in Evander, 60 miles east of
Johannesburg.
   But the National Union of Mineworkers said the company ``used
live bullets to intimidate union members who had been involved in
protest action against the general election, and management were
using mine security to assault workers'' taking part in a nationwide
work stoppage.
   The union said security guards opened fire on workers who wanted
to ask them to stop the assaults, killing the three.
</TEXT>
