<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     09-09 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says He'll Address United Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat will fly to
New York to call on the U.N. General Assembly to convene an
international peace conference on the Middle East, a newspaper
quoted him Saturday as saying.
   Last year, Washington denied Arafat a visa, prompting the world
body to move to Geneva to hear the Palestinian leader.
   ``I am going to New York to discuss the convening of the
international conference'' on Middle East peace, Arafat was quoted
as telling the daily newspaper Asharq Al-Awsat.
   Arafat appeared confident he will be allowed to enter the United
States to address the United Nations later this month.
   Mark Dillen, a State Department spokesman, said Saturday that
``as far as we know he has made no visa application.''
   On Friday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told reporters
after a meeting with Secretary of State James A. Baker III that his
government would view issuance of a U.S. visa to Arafat ``very
gravely.''
   During last year's session in Geneva, the 60-year-old Arafat
openly renounced terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist,
encouraging the United States to end a 13-year ban on dealings with
the Palestine Liberation Organization and to begin a dialogue with
the movement.
   Asharq Al-Awsat said it interviewed the Palestinian leader in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, this week during a summit of 102 non-aligned
nations. He said he was ``heading to New York with the leaders of
the nine states who met on sidelines of the non-aligned summit
conference ... to discuss the international peace conference with
the U.N. secretary-general and the permanent members of the Security
Council.''
   Egypt is spearheading Arab efforts to persuade Washington not to
block Arafat's intended visit, despite pressures by Israel.
Palestinian sources have said Arafat would offer new peace proposals
in his address.
   Arafat told Asharq Al-Awsat that convening an international
conference as envisaged by Arab leaders ``is not going to be easy as
some might think, because nothing comes on a silver platter.''
   He said he discussed the issue with U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar at the Belgrade summit that ended Friday.
   Arafat charged the United States is proving ``intransigent'' in
the peace process by ignoring Arab proposals and supporting only
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's election plan.
   A Palestinian uprising, funded and largely directed by the PLO,
has been under way in the West Bank and Gaza Strip for 21 months,
resulting in the deaths of more than 550 Palestinians and more than
35 Israelis.
   The PLO has rejected Shamir's proposal for elections in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to allow Palestinians to choose
their own representatives to negotiate with Israel. Arafat insists
on an Israeli withdrawal from the territories and international
supervision of these elections.
   But Arafat said he has detected ``positive indicators on the
horizon'' because President Bush has referred to the need to end the
Israeli occupation and Secretary of State James A. Baker III has
spoken of ``something similar.''
</TEXT>
