<SECOND>AM-BRF--Disabled Rocker,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraplegic Musician Charges Club With Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paraplegic rock 'n' roll musician who
alleged that the popular rock club the Troubadour refused to book
his act has filed a discrimination complaint with the state.
   ``They told me they'd heard I had a following of 50 wheelchair
groupies coming to watch me perform and they couldn't have that
stampede,'' Dorik Perman said. He complained to the state Department
of Fair Employment and Housing.
   Perman, 34, has been disabled since childhood by muscular
dystrophy. But he has earned favorable reviews as a rock 'n' roller,
playing such Los Angeles clubs as the Roxy, Gazzarri's and Club
Lingerie.
   Troubadour officials denied they discriminated against Perman.
   ``He does not have a following, and those who don't, we don't
book. That's just business,'' said Gina Barsamian, who is in charge
of bookings for the club. She added that the club has no ramp or
room for wheelchairs on stage, so ``This would be for his own
safety, too.''
