<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Chapin     09-09 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Chapin,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Official Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederic L. Chapin, a former U.S. ambassador to
Ethiopia and Guatemala who also served as a special envoy to El
Salvador in 1981, died of cancer, his family said Saturday.
   Chapin, who was 60, died at Johns Hopkins University Hospital in
Baltimore on Friday.
   A career foreign service officer who held several posts at the
State Department, Chapin also was a deputy assistant secretary of
defense in 1980 under President Carter.
   A native of New York City, Chapin graduated from Harvard
University in 1950 and joined the foreign service in 1952. Among,
his State Department assignments in Washington he was executive
secretary of the Agency for International Development in 1965-66 and
he served in embassies in Vienna, Managua and Chad.
   He was U.S. ambassador to Ethiopia from 1978 to 1980 and was
ambassador to Guatemala from 1981 to 1984.
   Chapin was the American charges d'affaires in San Salvador in
1981, representing the United States there before then-President
Reagan named an ambassador.
   He retired in 1988 as a senior inspector at the State Department.
</TEXT>
