<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     09-09 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel Appeals To Polish, Hungarian Reformers for Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's most prominent human
rights activist has appealed to Polish Prime Minister Tadeusz
Mazowiecki and leading Hungarian reformer Imre Pozsgay to help free
two Slovak activists.
   In an open letter, Vaclav Havel told Mazowiecki and Pozsgay that
they might well be in jail rather than in leading positions if they
lived in today's Czechoslovakia. He begged them to speak out for Jan
Carnogursky and Miroslav Kusy.
   The two were arrested last month and could face up to 10 years in
jail if convicted on subversion charges. They were arrested for
signing a document calling for a silent protest on the anniversary
of the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed reforms in Prague.
   ``I cannot imagine that the efforts of your countries to create a
democratic and pluralistic society could be permanently successful
if Czechoslovakia were to remain stuck between Poland and Hungary
like a dark wedge, a country which ... imprisons probably more
critics of its leadership than in (late Soviet President Leonid I.)
Brezhnev's time,'' he wrote.
   Havel's letter was written Friday and made available by the
London-based emigre publishing house Palach Press.
   Havel, who was jailed for four months earlier this year, compared
Kusy, a former senior Communist Party official, to Pozsgay. He
likened Carnogursky, a leading Roman Catholic lay activist, to
Poland's new non-Communist premier.
   To Mazowiecki, the playwright noted that ``if the situation in
Czechoslovakia developed toward democracy, it cannot be ruled out
that one day, Jan Carnogursky might be holding the same post with
which you have been entrusted in Poland.''
   Both Carnogursky and Kusy repeatedly have been harassed and
detained for their role as Charter 77 human rights activists.
   Hungary and Poland have embraced democratic reform while
Czechoslovakia has resisted change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
