<FIRST>r i AM-India-Guerrillas     09-09 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Guerrillas,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribal Guerrillas Kill 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separatist guerrillas raided a remote
border village in northeastern India and killed 12 people, Press
Trust of India reported Saturday.
   Friday night's attack by militants of the Bodo tribe also left at
least 27 people injured in the village of Bokajali in Assam state,
the news agency said. The village is about 800 miles east of New
Delhi.
   The agency said all the victims were native Assamese whose houses
were burned in the raid.
   The latest deaths bring to 20 the number of people killed in the
past week by Bodo guerrillas fighting for a separate homeland in
Assam, a hilly state bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   Police are searching nearby forests where the attackers are
believed to have fled, Press Trust said.
   Bodo militants pressed their demands for more than 20 years, then
took up arms two years ago. At least 270 people have been killed in
the violence this year.
   The government refuses to consider their tribal demand, but held
unsuccessful peace talks last year with militants who allege they
are discriminated against by the state's majority Assamese people.
   Bodos are mostly farmers who were animists before they converted
earlier this century to Christianity and Hindusim, India's dominant
religion. They are 30 percent of Assam's 20 million people.
</TEXT>
