<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Glemp 1stLd-Writethru a0531 09-09 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Glemp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Primate Cancels Trip To United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with reaction from Jewish, Polish groups in Chicago.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic primate Jozef Glemp, who has
been at the center of a dispute over a convent at the Auschwitz
death camp, has canceled a planned trip to the United States, the
state news agency reported Saturday.
   The PAP agency said the leader of Poland's Catholic Church is
postponing his visit because of ``circumstances not favorable'' for
the trip. It did not refer to the controversy over the convent.
   The primate has been at the center of the dispute over the
presence of Carmelite nuns at the site of the Nazi death camp. The
convent is in a former warehouse just outside the camp site.
   Glemp was to visit Chicago, Cleveland, Milwaukee, Detroit,
Washington and Boston beginning Sept. 21.
   The Polish church did not meet a Feb. 22 deadline to move the
convent to an interfaith center as agreed under a 1987 accord
reached by Catholic and Jewish leaders.
   Many Jews and others view the nuns' presence as an offensive
intrusion of Christian symbols at a place where 2.5 million Jews
were murdered by the Nazis during World War II.
   Glemp's efforts to calm the dispute, which has brought protesters
to the convent, backfired when he said the pact should be
renegotiated. He also said in an Aug. 26 sermon that Polish
anti-Semitism would disappear if Jews would abandon anti-Polish
sentiments.
   Glemp also angered many by suggesting Jews helped spread
communism, and by mentioning that some collaborated with Nazis
during World War II.
   The primate and a Polish church commission have urged more talks
without preconditions to resolve the future of the convent.
   Efforts to move the convent have found little sympathy among many
Poles, who say 1.5 million Christians also were killed at the site.
   In Chicago, leaders of the Polish and Jewish communities praised
Glemp's decision to call off the trip. Jewish leaders said remarks
made by Glemp about the convent had strained relations to the
breaking point.
   Michael Kotzin, director of the Jewish Community Relations
Council, said in a telephone interview, ``Now we in this community
have the opportunity for quiet attempts to deal with tensions in
Polish-Jewish and Catholic-Jewish relations.''
   Chicago Alderman Roman Pucinski, head of the Illinois division of
the Polish-American Congress, also praised Glemp for his decision.
   ``In view of the worldwide controversy that the Auschwitz camp
has developed into, I'm sure that the cardinal is doing a very wise
thing,'' Pucinski said in a telephone interview. ``It's an explosive
situation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
