<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Honecker     09-09 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Honecker,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Leader Reported Recovering in Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker is
weak but recovering in a hospital from successful gallbladder
surgery, a West German magazine reported Saturday.
   The Hamburg-based Der Spiegel, quoting unidentified sources in
East Berlin, said the Communist leader was being treated in a
hospital outside his country's capital.
   The report contradicted recent reports from state-run East German
media that the 77-year-old Honecker had been released from the
hospital and was recovering at home after the surgery.
   Spiegel also said doctors are concerned about the condition of
Honecker's liver and a kidney. It did not elaborate.
   East German reports have not elaborated on Honecker's medical
problems. Previous Western news reports have speculated the
hard-line Communist leader was suffering from cancer.
   In its report, Spiegel said Honecker ``will eventually be able to
return to work but will not regain his previous energy.''
   West German officials have said Honecker's illness has hampered
efforts to resolve a diplomatic crisis over a flood of East Germans
seeking to emigrate to the West. Most of them are in Hungary
awaiting permission to travel into Austria.
</TEXT>
