<FIRST>u a AM-YeltsinVisit 2ndLd-Writethru a0540 09-09 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin Visit, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0540,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Politician Makes First U.S. Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Yeltsin arrival; changes length
of stay to two weeks sted 10 days, reflecting official change. Picks up
5th graf pvs, `We expect...'. SUBS 9-11th grafs pvs, bgng `An invitation...',
to revise date of departure, reflecting change, add cities to list of planned
appearances, other detail. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `It's not..'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the gadfly in Mikhail
Gorbachev's ointment, arrived Saturday for his first visit to the
United States _ a two-week national tour featuring the Soviet
political maverick's views on glasnost and government.
   ``I want to see the Washington Monument, Library of Congress and
other cultural treasures of the United States,'' Yeltsin said at an
impromptu news conference at Kennedy International Airport.
   ``I also want to meet with you. ... I'm meeting with businessmen,
politicians and universities,'' Yeltsin said through a translator.
``It's a good opportunity to visit your country.''
   Yeltsin, wearing a blue suit with a Soviet flag on the lapel, was
presented with a bouquet of roses upon his arrival by
representatives of the Esalen Institute, which invited him as part
of its Soviet-American exchange program.
   As he moved through the airport, Yeltsin got a taste of Western
life _ a greeting from a Hare Krishna follower who gave him two
books and two roses.
   ``It's kind of a little thanks for the changes in the Soviet
Union,'' said David Jakupko, director of Soviet affairs for the Hare
Krishnas worldwide.
   The visit brings Gorbachev's most vocal critic to the U.S. and
caps Yeltsin's comeback from political outcast to populist hero.
   ``He's in a class by himself. He has an enormous vitality. He's
an iconoclast ... He's become a symbol of resentment against party
bureaucrats,'' said Marshall Shulman, an adviser to Carter
administration Secretary of State Cyrus Vance and a Soviet expert.
   On Monday, he is to deliver a luncheon address to the Council on
Foreign Relations, followed by an evening speech at Columbia
University.
   ``We expect Boris will be on `Good Evening America' or `Good
Morning America' _ whatever it is,'' said Yeltsin's chief aide, Lev
Sukhanov.
   Two years ago, Yeltsin was booted from his post as Moscow's
Communist Party chief after he criticized the slow pace of reform
under Gorbachev.
   But Yeltsin thrived after his dismissal. He campaigned for a seat
in the Soviet Congress, and in March was swept into office with more
than 90 percent of the popular vote in the first contested Soviet
election since 1917. He now heads the Soviet Union's radical bloc of
legislators.
   Yeltsin, 58, through an intermediary, sent word earlier this year
to the Leigh Bureau in Princeton, N.J., that he was interested in
coming to the United States, said Bill Leigh, head of the speakers
agency.
   An invitation was extended via Esalen and the final details
worked out the first week in August, Leigh said. Yeltsin's visit may
also have a capitalist purpose: Yeltsin has a book deal with a U.S.
publisher, Shulman said, although Yeltsin plans to donate his
speaking fees to a Soviet fund to fight AIDS and said he hoped to
visit AIDS clinics.
   Yeltsin is scheduled to leave Sept. 23; in the meantime, he'll
stay busy.
   Appearances have already been announced in New York,
Philadelphia, Chicago, Indianapolis, Minneapolis, Baltimore, Dallas,
Miami and Washington, although Leigh said his exact schedule was not
set.
   It's not clear if Yeltsin plans to criticize Gorbachev during his
visit _ Leigh would only say his Columbia speech concerned ``the
future of Soviet democracy.''
   Shulman believes Yeltsin will tread lightly when it comes to
criticizing the Soviet leader while in this country.
   ``He is conscious of the fact that Gorbachev is in a difficult
position. He supports Gorbachev, but he would like Gorbachev to move
along more quickly with reform,'' Shulman said.
   ``My guess is he will be constrained in his criticism, but it's
hard to predict. He's a mercurial man.''
</TEXT>
