<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Cowper     09-09 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Cowper,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Spill Gave Alaska Governor National Spotlight, But Future Uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Steve Cowper got his first word about
the nation's worst oil spill while he was telling an interviewer
that he had decided not to run for re-election.
   Since then, he's had little time to think about life beyond the
governor's mansion.
   Cowper announced his decision March 24, coincidentally the same
day the tanker Exxon Valdez ripped its hull open on a reef and
spilled nearly 11 million gallons of North Slope crude oil into
Prince William Sound.
   The disaster has defined his political life ever since.
   In recent weeks, Cowper has been lobbying Congress and seeking
support from other governors for federal laws to improve the
nation's response to major oil spills.
   ``The major thing that we've learned as a result of the spill is
that this nation doesn't have the capability of cleaning up an oil
spill as big as this one,'' he said.
   Cowper would like to see the Coast Guard put in absolute charge
of any oil spill larger than 12,000 barrels, a national inventory of
spill equipment including some Soviet-class oil-skimming vessels,
and a trained corps of spill experts who can respond quickly.
   ``Speed is of the essence when you're responding to an oil spill
and you're standing around trying to figure out where the equipment
is,'' he said. ``An oil spill can get out of hand pretty quickly.
That's what happened in Prince William Sound.''
   The spill gave Cowper the kind of national exposure coveted by
any ambitious politician, and his frequent appearances on national
TV led to rumors that he was training his sites on a seat in
Congress. He has not ruled that out, but in a recent interview he
said he will take a long leave from politics when his four-year term
expires next year.
   ``I may come back for another try for elective office, but if I
do, I expect it will be years from now,'' said Cowper, who was due
back in the state during the weekend after a 10-day good will trip
to Siberia.
   ``If I had to make the decision right now, I'd say I'd never be
interested in going to Washington,'' he said. ``My impression is
that people don't enjoy those jobs anymore. They have to spend half
their time in useless activity and a lot of what's left over is
directed toward raising money.''
   Cowper, 50, moved to Alaska in 1968 but still speaks with the
distinctive drawl of his native Virginia. He worked as an attorney,
prosecutor, businessman, newspaper reporter, research diver,
arbitrator, state lobbyist and served two terms in the Alaska House
in the late 1970s. He was elected governor in 1986 after defeating
incumbent Gov. William Sheffield in the Democratic primary.
   Despite his varied career, many were surprised by his decision to
look for a new job in 1990.
   ``Actually, I have never even remotely considered running for a
second term,'' he said. ``I always did think that I was going to
serve for four years and step down. I was persuaded not to mention
it _ not till March.''
   At times the stress of being governor of this vast, oil-dependent
state has been evident on Cowper, who concedes: ``I don't have much
of a poker face.
   ``If I've looked anxious from time to time it's because Alaska's
gone through some very hard experiences while I've been in office.
   ``The economy had crashed, the government appeared to be in
crisis, the budget was in severe imbalance, we had an assortment of
emergencies including the oil spill. I had an organization in the
Senate for the first two years that was actively hostile to almost
everything that we wanted to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890909-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Denmark-Plane     09-09 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denmark-Plane,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Metal Fatigue Might Have Caused Plane Crash that Killed 55</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aviation specialists said Saturday
that metal fatigue might have caused the crash of a Norwegian
charter plane that plunged into the North Sea, killing all 55 people
aboard.
   The twin-engine CV-580 Convair turboprop was flying from Norway
to West Germany when it vanished from radar screens Friday and
crashed 18.5 miles north of the Danish fishing port of Hirtshals.
Whatever occurred happened so quickly the pilots had no time to send
a distress signal, according to investigators.
   Tommy Jensen, head of the Danish crash investigation team, was
quoted by the Norwegian NTB news agency as saying ``so far no burns
or other damage on bodies or wreckage has been found to indicate an
explosives blast. Bodies and wreckage were found within a
concentrated area whereas midair explosions usually scatter them.''
   Some victims were found still strapped in their seats that had
torn loose from the fuselage, he said.
   In Norway, political parties canceled the rest of the campaign
for national elections in mourning for the crash victims but the
balloting will be held Monday as scheduled.
   Rolf Grimsrud of Norway's Civil Aviation Board said parts of the
plane might have been ripped apart when cabin pressure dropped as
the craft arrived at its cruising altitude of about 23,000 feet. The
cause could have been metal fatigue in some section, he said,
indicating a bomb explosion was seen as unlikely though not ruled
out.
   All 50 passengers were employees of the Wilhelmsen Lines shipping
company of Oslo. They had been chosen by lottery for the free trip
to Hamburg, West Germany, to see a ship christened. The plane had a
crew of five.
   Officials initially said all of the victims were Norwegians. But
a company list, which reported there were 38 men and 17 women
aboard, said three of the women had British passports and were
living in Norway.
   Rescue officials reported late Saturday that 31 bodies had been
recovered and it was presumed the others were trapped in the
wreckage. They had reported Friday that 32 bodies had been found but
lowered that figures as the remains were brought ashore.
   The U.S.-built plane belonged to the Norwegian Partnair charter
airline company. The 35-year old aircraft had recently undergone a
major maintenance checkup in Canada, the airline said.
   Flight Supervisor Karl Andersen at Copenhagen's Kastrup Airport
was quoted by Danish radio as saying parts of the plane might have
broken off in flight. ``The radar signal disappeared very suddenly
from our screens, and the plane went down fast,'' he said.
   No other flights or flying objects were spotted on flight control
radar screens at the time, discounting the possibility of a
collision or the craft had been shot down, Andersen added.
   Officials said a fishing trawler participating in the search
received a sonar echo that could have been from the wreckage but
West German navy divers could not confirm that because of poor
visibility at the 90-yard depth.
   A Norwegian vessel with minisubmarines was on its way to the area
to help locate the wreckage, including the flight recorders,
according to officials.
   They said the effort to recover all of the bodies and complete
the salvage operation could take up to two weeks.
</TEXT>
