<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1630EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     09-09 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev, Back in Command After Vacation, Reassures Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, resuming command
after his summer vacation, on Saturday dismissed warnings of
impending chaos and assured Soviets his reforms are on track.
   Looking rested and slightly tanned, Gorbachev covered a wide
range of national issues in a half-hour speech on the nightly
television news program Vremya, including strikes, crime, shortages
and the need for ``the consolidation of all progressive forces'' to
further his reforms.
   He skirted the ethnic conflicts that are plaguing the Soviet
Union, and did not mention the recent Central Committee attack on
separatists in the Baltic republics or the weeklong strike in the
southern republic of Azerbaijan.
   ``Intimidation about impending chaos, and speculation about the
threat of a coup, even a civil war, can be heard,'' Gorbachev said.
``It's a fact that someone wants to create in society an atmosphere
of anxiety, hopelessness and insecurity.''
   But, Gorbachev assured viewers, ``We are building up and
deepening the changes that we started, and they will bring results.''
   Gorbachev last was seen in public in early August, and he was
presumed to be on vacation until this week. But an official Soviet
spokesman said the president was involved in a stinging Central
Committee statement on the Baltic republics two weeks ago warning
Baltic residents about nationalists who were going too far and
leading them into an abyss.
   Gorbachev also reportedly consulted by telephone at the time with
Lithuanian party chief Algirdas Brazauskas.
   On the explosive ethnic conflicts, Gorbachev said only that they
would be discussed at a plenum of the policy-setting Central
Committee. The plenum is expected this week or next week at the
latest, and Tass reported Saturday night that the ruling Politburo
met Friday and discussed ethnic issues to prepare for it.
   Gorbachev warned Saturday that strikes can have ``dangerous
consequences for society,'' and ``we should not tolerate the huge
economic losses'' they create.
   Hundreds of thousands of Soviet coal miners went on strike in
July to demand better conditions, and many workers in the southern
republic of Azerbaijan were on strike all this week to press for
control of the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   On crime, Gorbachev called for ``the strictest order'' in cities
and towns, and he praised informal crime-fighting groups.
   He said the government has to answer for shortages that steadily
have worsened in the last year, including such staples as sugar,
tea, butter and meat.
   Gorbachev warned that some measures taken to fix the economy
``might be unpopular, tough in some ways and painful to a certain
extent.''
   He defended the Communist Party, which has been under fire for
reacting too slowly to changes in Soviet society. He said the party
was ``overcoming its dogmatism and conservatism.''
   ``Those who hope to take advantage of difficulties of the period
of transition for some unsavory purposes and try to undermine the
party's influence should know that this will not work,'' he said.
   As he often has before, Gorbachev called for a middle road
between radicals who want to effect changes too fast and
conservatives who hope for a return to the past.
</TEXT>
