<FIRST>u i AM-Norway-Election     09-09 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Election,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway Calls off Election Campaign Because of Air Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Dennar-Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political parties on Saturday canceled the
rest of the campaign for national elections in mourning for victims
of a plane crash that killed 55 people in Norway's worst air
disaster.
   But Monday's elections will be held as scheduled.
   ``A major, tragic accident has hit our nation .... The only right
and proper thing to do is to end the campaign right now,'' Prime
Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland said late Friday.
   The Norwegian Convair CV-580 turboprop was en route to West
Germany from Oslo on Friday when it crashed into the ocean north of
Denmark, killing all aboard. Most of the passengers on the charter
flight were Norwegians who won a lottery at the shipping company
where they worked to see a ship christened in West Germany.
   The chairmen of Norway's seven largest parties agreed to cancel
the rest f the campaign out of respect for the victims.
   A poll published Saturday gave Mrs. Brundtland's socialist Labor
Party 33.7 percent of the vote, down from 40.8 percent in the
previous general election in 1985.
   The largest opposition party, the Conservatives, was picked by 20
percent of the polled voters. It had 30.4 percent of the vote in
1985.
   The right-wing Party of Progress had climbed from 3.7 percent of
the 1985 vote to 22 percent in a late August poll. However, it
slipped to 16.1 percent in Saturday's survey.
   Several other small parties gained support from the rest of the
voters in the telephone poll.
   The survey of 1,215 voters, with a 2.8 percent margin of error,
was published in the daily newspaper Aftenposten.
</TEXT>
