<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     09-09 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Stop Afghan Government Convoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-communist guerrillas have blocked
a 1,300-vehicle supply convoy outside a provincial capital, a senior
government official said Saturday.
   It was believed to be the biggest convoy of the 10-year-old civil
war between the Marxist government and rebels.
   In Kabul, six people were killed and eight wounded by three
rockets, a government spokesman said.
   More than 300 people have been killed and 700 injured in almost
daily rocket attacks on the capital since late June. The government
blames the attacks on the Pakistan-based guerrillas, but the rebels
accuse the Soviet-backed government of firing on its own civilians.
   Deputy Prime Minister Mahmoud Baryalai said the huge supply
convoy was stopped short of the southern city of Kandahar by heavy
fighting.
   ``The opponents are not sitting idle,'' he said, and they knew
they would lose a crucial advantage if the supplies are delivered.
   Government officials have said the convoy, which left in late
August from the town of Torgundi near the Soviet border, is carrying
military and civilian supplies to keep Kandahar going through the
winter.
   Two days ago the government said the convoy was in Maywand, 36
miles east of the Kandahar.
   Baryalai said the rebels stopped the convoy with random rocket
attacks on the road.
   He again denied a rebel claim that 80 vehicles have been
destroyed. He said only three were lost.
   Around the eastern city of Khost, government forces repulsed an
attack on an outer defense line, the state news agency Bakhtar
reported.
   Diplomats said the battle for Khost appeared to be stalemated.
</TEXT>
