<SECOND>AM-BRF---Czechoslovakia-Albania,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Proposes Full Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government wants to restore
full diplomatic ties with Albania, cut in 1961 because of the Soviet
Union's break with Albania, the Communist Party daily Rude Pravo
said Saturday.
   By upgrading relations with an exchange of ambassadors,
Czechoslovakia would be following Hungary, East Germany, Romania and
Bulgaria.
   However, the isolated Communist leadership in the small Balkan
nation has refused Soviet overtures to restore ties severed because
of Albania's hard-line Stalinist and pro-Chinese stances.
   Rude Pravo said it was ``abnormal'' for Czechoslovakia and
Albania to maintain only charge d'affaires in each other's
countries. A note requesting improved ties was handed Friday to
Albanian charge d'affaires Idriz Dhrami, who said Saturday he had no
comment on the proposal.
</TEXT>
