<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-09 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Thunderstorms Across Southern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell Saturday across the southern Plains as showers
and thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front that stretched
from the southern Plains to the upper Great Lakes.
   Late Friday, severe thunderstorms hit parts of Missouri, Kansas
and Nebraska, and the heavy rain continued Saturday from southern
Texas across Arkansas and Kansas into southern Missouri.
   Eureka, Ark., got nearly 3 inches of rain in 6 hours during the
morning.
   The Kansas City, Mo., area got 4.5 inches of rain in the storms
from Friday into Saturday.
   Rivers and streams rose across northeastern Kansas, southeastern
Nebraska and northwestern Missouri.
   Minor flooding occurred along the Republican River near Clay
Center, Kan., and several rural roads in the area were closed by
water, the National Weather Service said.
   The Platte River at Platte City, Mo., is expected to rise to 10
feet above flood stage by Monday morning and the Missouri River at
St. Joseph, Mo., already 2 feet above flood stage, was expected to
climb 7 feet above flood stage, the weather service said.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the Tennessee
Valley and along the Gulf Coast, and showers extended from Iowa into
the upper Great Lakes.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
1.06 inches at Milwaukee and 1.02 inches at Springfield, Mo.
   Cool, moist air pushing into the northern and central Rockies
produced showers, with snow at higher elevations. In Wyoming, up to
5 inches of snow fell across the Wind River range and the Laramie
Range received a half-inch of snow.
   Afternoon temperatures were only in the 40s and 50s from the
northern and central Rockies across much of North Dakota into
northern Minnesota.
   Great Falls, Mont., tied its record low for the date of 31
degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Riverton, Wyo., to 98 at Harlingen, Waco and Austin,
Texas, and Palm Springs, Calif. Saturday morning's low in the Lower
48 states was 26 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the
eastern half of the southern Plains and the lower Mississippi Valley
across the Ohio Valley and the eastern half of the Great Lakes
region to northern New England. Scattered showers were forecast from
the northern Plains and Nebraska into the northern and central
Rockies. Snow was forecast at higher elevations of the northern
Rockies.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted over northwestern and central
Montana; in the 50s and 60s from Idaho across Wyoming, the northern
Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley to the western half of the
upper Great Lakes region; in the 90s from the southern Atlantic
Coast and Florida across the Tennessee Valley and the Gulf Coast to
southern and eastern Texas; between 90 and 105 across the desert
Southwest into interior valleys of California; and in the 70s and
80s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
