<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovak-Church     09-09 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Church,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 30,000 Attend Bishop's Consecration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 30,000 people attended the
consecration Saturday of the new Roman Catholic bishop in the Slovak
diocese of Spis, the Catholic news agency Kathpress reported.
   The new bishop, Frantisek Tondra, is one of four named by the
Vatican in July after years of negotations with Czechoslovakia's
communist government.
   Tondra, a 53-year-old former parish priest, is the first bishop
appointed in the diocese of Spis in almost four decades. The last
resident bishop there was Jan Vojtassak, who in 1951 was sentenced
to 24 years in jail, according to Kathpress. It gave no further
information about Vojtassak.
   Kathpress said that a Vatican envoy, Archbishop Francesco
Colasuonno, the other Czechoslovak bishops and Vienna's bishop Kurt
Krenn were among those attending the consecration ceremony.
   Seven of Czechoslovakia's 13 dioceses are still without bishops,
and the Catholic church has said not enough priests are allowed to
train at the country's three seminaries to fill vacant parishes.
   In May 1988, the Vatican selected the first three bishops
appointed in 15 years in Czechoslovakia, but none was a residential
bishop. Those appointments and the July announcement followed
intense negotiations and a petition for more bishops, priests and
religious freedom signed in early 1988 by more than half a million
Czechoslovaks.
</TEXT>
