<FIRST>r i AM-Noriega-US     09-09 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noriega-US,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Congressaen Calls Noriega `Narco-Terrorist'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOWARD AIR BASE, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-member U.S. congressional
delegation on Saturday accused Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who
controls the Panamanian government, of being a ``narco-terrorist.''
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., told a news conference that the
United States will continue its efforts to oust Noriega and will
``increase pressure against him and his associates in areas such as
preventing their travel to the United States and preventing their
conducting business with the United States.''
   He was referring to recent U.S. measures aimed at further
isolating the Panamanian government economically by forbidding U.S.
companies from doing business with Noriega's associates.
   ``Noriega's involvement in drug dealing and money laundering, for
which he faces indictment before U.S. courts, makes him a premier
narco-terrorist,'' Edwards said in a statement. ``From the streets
of American cities to the unfolding drama in Panama's neighbor to
the south (Colombia), we can see the effects of men like Noreiga
choosing power and profit over principle.''
   His statement said the United States will ``stand by the people
of Panama until their fight for self-determination is respected and
democratic government is restored.'' It also said the United States
will continue to ``oppose any accommodation with any regime or
official appointed by Noriega.''
   Noriega, commander of Panama's Defense Forces, was indicted by
two federal grand juries in Florida in February 1988. They accused
him of dealing in illegal narcotics including laundering drug money.
   The congressmen came to this Air Force base, part of the U.S.
Southern Command, from El Salvador. They left Saturday for Nicaragua.
   They met with former presidential candidate Guillermo Endara and
his vice presdiential running mate Guillermo Ford, whom they called
``the elected leadership of this country.''
   International oberservers said opposition candidates Endara and
Ford won the May 7 elections, but the government annulled the
balloting, saying U.S. financial assistance and other support for
the opposition distorted the election results.
   Edwards declined to say if he thought the United States should
recognize Endara as president, as it did ousted President Eric
Delvalle.
   ``That is a decision for President Bush and Mr. Endara,'' Edwards
said. ``The world is full of presidents in exile. We do not want a
president who does not hold power.... It is not up to the United
States to put an elected president in power ... that is up to the
Panamanian people.''
   Noriega has denied all U.S. allegations against him and claims
the United States want to remove him and renege on the Panama Canal
Treaties that turn the canal over Panama at the end of the century.
   Other members of the congressional delegation are Doug Bereuter,
R-Neb., Bill Grant, D-Fla. and Elton Gallegly, R-Calif.
</TEXT>
