<FIRST>r a AM-StarvationTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0578 09-09 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Starvation Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0578,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal on Religious Grounds Planned in Starvation Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to RESTORE first name of Cottam, picks up 4th
graf, ``They were...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ Attorneys for a Seventh-day Adventist
couple convicted of starving their teen-age son to death say they
will appeal the verdict on grounds the boy was expressing his
freedom of religion.
   Fourteen-year-old Eric Cottam died Jan. 3 after the family went
six weeks without food despite $3,775 set aside by Eric's father, a
former Seventh-day Adventist Church pastor, as a tithe for God.
   A jury on Friday deliberated for less than two hours before
finding Larry Cottam and his wife, Leona Cottam, guilty of
third-degree murder, two counts each of recklessly endangering
another person and endangering the welfare of children in the cases
of Eric and their 12-year-old daughter, Laura, who since has been
placed in a foster home.
   ``They were under the care, control and custody of their parents
... Even though they may not want to eat, the parents' duty
supercedes,'' Luzerne County Judge Gifford S. Cappelini said after
the verdict.
   The family had contended that each member agreed to the fast
because of their religious convictions. But Cappelini ruled the
Cottams couldn't raise the children's religious freedom in front of
the jury.
   Al Flora Jr., an attorney for the Cottams, said he plans to
appeal on the grounds the children's constitutional rights to
religious freedom were not considered by the jury because of
Cappelini's ruling.
   ``Some of the issues involved in this case are novel ones,''
Flora said in asking the judge to allow the Cottams to remain free
on bail pending appeal. ``They are issues that have not been taken
up by our appellate courts.''
   Cottam, 39, and Mrs. Cottam, 38, remain free on $50,000 bail
each. An anonymous benefactor posted bail for them Aug. 23 after
they spent 230 days in custody following their Jan. 5 arraignment at
Mercy Hospital.
   After he was arrested, Cottam told police he couldn't spend the
nearly $4,000 in tithe money for food because it belonged to God.
Spending it would have been akin to stealing, he said.
   Seventh-day Adventists generally give 10 percent of their
earnings as a tithe, but a church official testified at the trial
tithing was not a requirement for membership in the church.
   Mrs. Cottam testified she had several dollars saved as a tithe,
but also believed spending the money for food would have been the
same as stealing.
   Neither Cottam or his wife commented following the verdict, nor
did they testify during the trial.
   No sentencing date has been set. They face a maximum 28 years in
prison.
   Eric Cottam died in an upstairs bedroom of the family's modest
two-story home in Nuangola, just south of this northeastern
Pennsylvania city. His 5-foot, 9-inch frame weighed 69 pounds.
   A day later, Larry Cottam went to a neighbor's house to call
police to his home. He, his wife and daughter were hospitalized for
malnutrition.
   Flora said the family went without food because they distrusted
authorities and believed God would rescue them from their plight.
They also believed their children would be taken away from them if
they sought help, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
