<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Hookers-Licenses     09-09 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hookers-Licenses,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cops Take Driver Licenses From Prostitutes' Customers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have begun suspending the
drivers' licenses of people caught soliciting prostitutes.
   Police say the license suspension is worse than the standard $500
fine for the crime, which most offenders pay after pleading guilty
rather than risk the public embarrassment of a trial.
   ``The fine isn't bad, but when they risk losing their driver
license, it takes on a whole new light,'' said police Sgt. Robb
Robertson.
   Police arrested 23 men for soliciting prostitutes last week and
issued the license revocation charge.
   ``They were not happy,'' Lt. David Hughes said. ``I think it will
have a good deterrent effect.''
   The law, which says violators making a deal for sex from a car
can lose their licenses for one year, was dormant for years and
re-enacted this year.
</TEXT>
