<HEAD>Man Raises Stink _ He's Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who raised a stink at a grocery
store was arrested when he refused to leave.
   Employees at Buttrey's called police early Friday when a man
reeking of skunk fumes came in and wouldn't leave.
   The man apparently had a run-in with a skunk as it was rummaging
for food behind the store, police said.
   The man went inside to get some tomato juice to rid himself of
the smell, but store workers and several customers turned up their
noses at him and asked him to leave.
   When officers arrived, the man was in the store and attempting to
shower in tomato juice, said Capt. Dale Brunson.
   Belva Williams, 29, of Richland, was cited by police for
trespassing and for being a public nuisance.
   Williams spent the night at Benton County Jail, after showering
with disinfectant and having his clothes laundered, police said.
   A judge released him later Friday morning without bail.
