<HEAD>Honduran Soldiers Killed In Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE number of injured, clarify tupe of
copter; No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bolt of lightning downed a
helicopter during U.S.-Honduran military maneuvers, killing four
Honduran soldiers and injuring four, the government said Saturday.
   Military sources said the accident occurred Friday night during a
heavy thunderstorm near the small village of San Antonio de Majada,
180 miles northeast of Tegucigalpa. The source said the Honduran air
force Bell-124 chopper was returning to the air base at San Pedro
Sula, 120 miles north of Tegucigalpa.
   The victims were identified as Lt. Col. Daniel Arturo Tabora
Talbot, Lt. Col. Wilfredo Mendoza Garay, Capt. Luis Felipe Reyes and
Lt. Nelson Henriiquez.
   The military said that three soldiers and the pilot were
hospitalized in stable condition on Saturday.
   Police and soldiers began recovering the bodies Saturday morning.
   The camouflaged helicopter and its occupants were participating
in the aerial part of the joint exercises, which conclude on Sept.
12. Military sources said 1,300 American and 2,700 Honduran soldiers
are participating in the maneuvers.
