<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 2113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugsPoll     09-09 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs Poll,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newsweek: Three of Four Would Raise Taxes to Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of Americans think President Bush
is shortchanging his anti-drug program and nearly three out of four
favor higher taxes on cigarettes and alcohol to pay for it,
according to a Newsweek poll released Saturday.
   Fifty-two percent of those polled said the anti-drug program
announced by Bush this week ``proposes spending too little money for
such a big problem,'' although 83 percent agreed ``it was a good
first step.''
   To pay for an anti-drug program, the poll showed that 73 percent
would support raising federal taxes on cigarettes and alcoholic
beverages and 65 percent said they would support a 1 percent surtax
on corporate income taxes.
   But 63 percent would oppose a 1 percent surtax on personal income
tax for the same purpose, the poll found.
   The poll showed that 86 percent of Americans say they would be
willing to take random, voluntary drug tests. Sixty-two percent
would support mandatory drug tests for public school students, while
36 percent would oppose this measure.
   The Newsweek poll, conducted by the Gallup Organization,
interviewed 609 adults Sept. 7-8. The margin of error is plus or
minus 4 percentage points.
</TEXT>
