<HEAD>Two Boys Drown in Kansas City; Indiana Woman Struck by Lightning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Missouri teen-agers drowned in separate incidents while
playing in flood-swollen waters, and at least seven people were
injured in Indiana, one by lightning, as a powerful thunderstorm
moved through Saturday.
   Bryan Hammer, 18, of Gladstone, Mo., was killed when he was
pulled into the 7-feet-deep Line Creek in Kansas City, Mo.,
authorities said.
   Hammer's roommate, Mike Marquez, said the two had gone to the
creek about midnight.
   ``We were out late and had nothing else to do, so we thought we'd
mess around in the water,'' Marquez said.
   Up to 4 inches of rain fell in the Kansas City area overnight.
   A 13-year-old North Kansas City boy died when he was swept into a
storm drain Friday night. Robert Ragsdale was pronounced dead about
7 p.m. at North Kansas City Hospital.
   Ragsdale and a friend ``were riding the drainage ditch like a
water slide and the water current just got too strong,'' said Bob
Jones, a spokesman for the Kansas City Police Department.
   In Indiana, the storm sparked flash flooding and cut electrical
power in Indianapolis.
   An unidentified 14-year-old girl was treated and released after
lightning struck near her during halftime of Saturday's football
game between Miami of Ohio and Purdue in Lafayette, officials said.
   And in New Palestine, between six and eight people received minor
injuries when gusting winds knocked down a tent at a festival,
police said.
