<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 2206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Algeria     09-09 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Algeria,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Premier Named in Algeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chadli Bendjedid, trying to
come to grips with a stubborn economic crisis, on Saturday sacked
his government and named a senior aide, Mouloud Hamrouche, as
Algeria's new premier.
   A communique issued by the presidency indicated Premier Kasdi
Merbah was removed because of the slow pace of political and
economic change, launched after riots swept the country in October,
1988. Merbah had been in office since November.
   The president called on the new premier to adopt the reforms,
which were approved in February. They were designed to transform
Algeria into a multiparty democracy from the one-party Socialist
state it has been since independence from France in 1962.
   Hamrouche, 46, had been Bendjedid's chief of staff since 1986.
   The new premier has extensive military and political experience.
At the age of 15, he joined the ruling National Liberation Army to
fight in Algeria's eight-year war for independence from France.
   He rose to the rank of lieutenant colonel, and earned degrees in
law and political science.
   In 1979, at the fourth congress of the National Liberation Front,
Hamrouche was elected an alternate member of the party Central
Committee. He became a full member at the next congress in 1984.
   He was named secretary-general of the government in 1984, and
chief of staff of the presidency in 1986.
   The job of premier will not be easy. Algeria is in the midst of a
severe economic crisis, in large part because of plummeting oil
prices. Petroleum is Algeria's only export.
   For years, oil income propped up Algeria's economy and paid for
imports of basic items such as wheat, milk and meat. The drop in oil
income in recent years has led to cuts in imports.
   Economic grievances sparked the 1988 riots in which 159 people
died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
