<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneFound     09-09 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Found,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wreckage of Missing Military Plane Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL TORO MARINE CORPS AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wreckage of a
military plane that disappeared more than two weeks ago was
discovered Saturday in the Southern California mountains, officials
said.
   Two bodies found at the scene were tentatively identified as the
two crew members from the reconnaissance plane, said Lt. Gene
Browne, spokesman for the El Toro base.
   The plane, an OV-10A assigned to the 3rd Marine Aircraft wing,
left Camp Pendleton on Aug. 24 for a three-hour mission and was
never heard from again.
   The plane was discovered in the San Gorgonio wilderness.
   San Bernardino County Sheriff's Department officials and the
military both took credit for finding the airplane.
   Sheriff's Sgt. Jim Singley spotted the crash site on the
5,300-foot-high ridge line of San Gorgonio Mountain between Banning
and Big Bear Lake, Bryant said. The San Gorgonio wilderness is 60
miles northeast of El Toro Marine Corps Air Station and about 90
miles east of Los Angeles.
   The mission crewmen were Capt. Sergio R. Vivaldi, 29, of Port
Chester, N.Y., the pilot, and 1st Lt. Joel H. Piehl, 31, of Fargo,
N.D., the observer.
   The aircraft was on a visual reconnaissance training mission that
could have covered an area from Camp Pendleton east toward the
Colorado River, north toward Las Vegas and south to the Mexican
border.
</TEXT>
