<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 2236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack     09-09 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Demonstrate Peacefully in Bensonhurst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 people marched through a New York City
neighborhood Saturday to protest again the racial slaying of a black
teen-ager, but this time the demonstration was peaceful.
   Also Saturday, an unarmed robbery suspect who was resisting
arrest died after being subdued by police officers, police said.
Witnesses said the man was kicked and beaten by the officers, who
shackled his hands and feet and then shouted insults and racial
epithets.
   In a similar protest staged a week ago in the New York City
borough of Brooklyn, residents of the predominantly white
Bensonhurst heckled, taunted and shoved the mostly black marchers.
   Residents Saturday refrained from violence and catcalls as they
watched the chanting, sign-carrying protesters.
   The demonstrators walked past the spot where Yusuf Hawkins, 16,
was shot and killed Aug. 23 after he and three friends were
surrounded by a group of whites carrying baseball bats and at least
one gun.
   Hawkins had gone to the neighborhood to look at a used car for
sale.
   Four white youths face murder charges in the case.
   In Saturday's incident, police said their initial investigation
into the death of Henry Hughes, 25, who is black, indicated he had
not been beaten.
   Assistant Chief John J. Holmes said Hughes was chased and caught
by the officers, then was ``fighting so strongly'' that they could
not get one set of handcuffs on him and had to use two handcuffs
linked together.
   A witness, Steven Perez, 27, said he was across the street and
saw three officers _ a woman and two men _ beating, kicking and
using nightsticks on the man for as long as an hour, while other
officers stood by.
   ``They killed him for no reason,'' said another witness, Victor
Vega, who said he was waiting at a bus stop when the suspect and
police ran by.
   Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the medical examiner's office,
said a preliminary examination of Hughes' body indicated no obvious
death-causing injuries.
</TEXT>
