<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0599 09-09 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Dale Ride obit. AM-Obit-Chapin moved as a0554.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederic L. Chapin, a former U.S. ambassador to
Ethiopia and Guatemala who also served as a special envoy to El
Salvador in 1981, died of cancer, his family said Saturday. He was
60.
   Chapin died at Johns Hopkins University Hospital in Baltimore on
Friday.
   A career foreign service officer who held several posts at the
State Department, Chapin also was a deputy assistant secretary of
defense in 1980 under President Carter.
   He was U.S. ambassador to Ethiopia from 1978 to 1980 and was
ambassador to Guatemala from 1981 to 1984.
   Chapin was the American charges d'affaires in San Salvador in
1981, representing the United States there before then-President
Reagan named an ambassador.
   He retired in 1988 as a senior inspector at the State Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dale Ride, the father of space
shuttle astronaut Sally Ride and a California State University
trustee, died Saturday from an apparent embolism. He was 67.
   Ride died at 1 a.m. at Santa Monica Hospital, following prostate
surgery, his wife Joyce said. An autopsy was scheduled to determine
the exact cause of death.
   Ride, an Encino resident, was assistant superintendent of
government relations at Santa Monica College. In 1984, Ride was
appointed to the California Board of Trustees of the California
State University system. He served as board president in 1988.
   His daughter Sally Ride became the first American woman to fly in
space in June 1983 on a six-day mission on the space shuttle
Challenger.
</TEXT>
