<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 2307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BoiseViolence 4thLd-Writethru a0613 09-09 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boise Violence, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0613,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Union Demonstration Erupts In Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to RECASTS lead and CORRECT that taverns
and liquors stores asked not to sell liquor, sted close. Picks up 8th graf,
`You don't...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DUL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas to turn
back demonstrators who burned temporary housing and overturned cars
Saturday in a protest of the hiring of non-union construction labor
at a Boise Cascade paper mill.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich put the National Guard on alert for possible
duty in the usually peaceful town on the Canadian border. But the
crowd, estimated at 400 in the morning, dwindled by afternoon and
city officials said the violence had ended.
   Police Chief Tom Hardy said officers used tear gas to turn back
the crowd and witnesses said protesters threw rocks at security
guards. A police dispatcher said several vehicles were overturned at
the housing camp about a mile from the construction site.
   Five people were treated at Memorial Hospital for various
injuries and released, said hospital administrator Randy Olson.
Koochiching County Sheriff Bill Elliott said 32 people were arrested
on charges of criminal damage to property and contempt of court.
   The violence stemmed from Boise's hiring of a non-union general
contractor for a $535 million expansion project at the paper mill, a
move that sparked a wildcat strike by union members in July. Since
then the company has been hit by sporadic violence including an
arson fire that caused an estimated $250,000 damage.
   Police expected to make more arrests after reviewing videotapes
of the violence, Elliott said.
   Mayor Jack Murray, in a statement read to local radio stations
Saturday morning, urged the town's 6,500 residents to stay in their
homes and asked bars and liquor stores not to serve liquor that day.
   ``You don't have a lot of control in this situation,'' Elliott
said. ``The people involved in it showed no respect for the law or
for International Falls.''
   About 45 officers from several jurisdictions were on hand, he
said, but ``we could have had all the police manpower in northern
Minnesota and still it wouldn't have been enough.''
   Union officials say they have tried to dissuade protesters from
violence or mass demonstrations in International Falls. There was no
immediate comment Saturday from Brad Skarich, president of the Iron
Range Building Trades Council, and Bill Peterson, head of the
Minnesota Building Trades Council; Skarich did not return a message
left on his home answering machine and there was no answer at
Peterson's office.
   Protesters pushed through a gate at a temporary housing complex
being set up for construction workers and tore down part of the
fence surrounding the camp.
   Boise Cascade spokesman Bob Anderson said eight to 10 mobile
homes in the camp were destroyed, including some that were ``totally
burned to the ground.'' He estimated that the facility, intended to
eventually house about 1,000 people and include a cafeteria, was 60
percent destroyed.
   The 100 workers already living there were removed Friday night in
anticipation of trouble, Anderson said. Boise also canceled work
Saturday at the project, he said.
   Police as a precaution Saturday morning evacuated an apartment
building leased largely to workers hired by BE&amp;K, the construction
project's general contractor, said police Capt. Randy Borden. He
could not say how many people were evacuated.
   ``The building trade activists from the area have just gone
berserk,'' said Anderson.
   ``It was non-union and racially motivated,'' Anderson said.
``People destroyed property and went after lives. We've had many
people threatened. It's been building trades activists that are just
acting as terrorists.''
   Anderson said a black family was threatened Saturday and the
company moved them inside the plant for protection. Police were
previously called to a Mexican-American family's home after an arson
threat, he said.
   He said there had been complaints that the company was only
hiring blacks and Hispanics.
   Borden said three black people were the targets of ``a lot of
name-calling and yelling'' when the apartment building was
evacuated. He said racial elements ``certainly come forth when
there's a confrontation, but how much that motivates it, I'm not in
any position to evaluate.''
   Elliott dismissed allegations that the riots had any racial
overtones. ``Someone might have made a remark about blacks,'' he
said, but added that racism wasn't linked to the rioting.
   By 6 p.m., state officials sent to International Falls told
Perpich that the situation was under control and that ``it is not
necessary to move additional resources into the area at the present
time,'' according to a statement from the governor's office. Guard
members will remain on standby, the statement said.
   Anderson complained that the governor was ``playing politics''
and siding with labor by not immediately sending National Guardsmen,
only putting them on alert. Although the situation had calmed by
afternoon, Anderson said protesters were drinking and he thought
more violence could erupt.
   Anderson said Saturday's protesters had come from North Dakota,
Wisconsin and Michigan.
</TEXT>
