<FIRST>r a AM-IowaLetter     09-09 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Letter,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor's Letter Says Iowa Crew Doesn't Believe Hartwig Caused Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iowa Inquiry, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors aboard the USS Iowa don't believe
Clayton M. Hartwig caused the explosion on the ship that killed 47
sailors, according to a letter sent to Hartwig's sister and revealed
Saturday.
   The Pentagon released a report Thursday on the gun turret
explosion that said circumstantial evidence indicated Hartwig
intentionally caused the blast. Hartwig, a gunner's mate, died in
the April 19 explosion.
   Kathleen Kubicina, Hartwig's sister, said she got a letter dated
Aug. 27 from a sailor she would identify only as ``Tom'' that said
crew members did not believe Hartwig was capable of causing the
explosion.
   ``The people on board who knew him believe as I do that the idea
of Clay being capable of such a crime is insane,'' the sailor wrote.
``I don't know what the reults of the investigation will be, but it
will not change mine or a lot of this crew's minds as to what we
believe could never have happened because we knew Clay.''
   Ms. Kubicina said the author's mother would not allow her son's
last name to be released for fear of retaliation from the Navy. Ms.
Kubicina provided a copy of the letter to The Associated Press.
   The Iowa left its Norfolk, Va., homeport in June for six months
in the Mediterranean Sea.
   ``When I first read it I felt this incredible relief,'' Ms.
Kubicina said. ``Even though it was written before the report was
released, it shows a lot of the guys support our position. It made a
world of difference to know the guys support me.''
   Ms. Kubicina and Hartwig's father, Earl, have said they believe
the Navy sought a scapegoat and blamed Hartwig for the explosion
that caused the biggest loss of live in the Navy since the Vietnam
War.
   Ms. Kubicina said the family planned to file a defamation of
character lawsuit against the Navy for alleging Hartwig may have
caused the explosion.
   ``We will file because this has caused undue emotional distress
to the family,'' she said.
</TEXT>
