<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-UN     09-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-UN,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Observers Reach Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. observers arrived in Honduras
Saturday and prepared to make plans for monitoring the
demobilization of U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras.
   About 12,000 Contras and their dependents are living in bases in
Honduras near the Nicaraguan border. Some have expressed reluctance
at accepting the demobilization, agreed to under a peace plan signed
by five Central American presidents in August.
   The observers are to watch over the voluntary repatriation or
relocation of the Contras, who have been fighting the Sandinista
government since 1982. The demobilization is to be completed before
year's end.
   Eugenio Castro Claramount, Foreign Ministry spokesman, said the
first group of U.N. observers to arrive included 18 civilians and
soldiers from Brazil, Canada, Fiji, Ireland, Peru, Spain, Sweden and
Venezuela.
   Castro Claramount said the observewrs were arriving on commercial
and military flights and the entire group should be in Honduras by
Sunday.
   The commission members will travel Monday by helicopter and land
to areas along the border with El Salvador and Nicaragua to inspect
the area. Castro Calarmount said the observers will meet with
Honduran officials Wednesday.
   Presidents Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala, Alfredo Cristiani of El
Salvador, Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras, Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua
and Oscar Arias of Costa Rica signed the agreement on Aug. 7.
   U.N. personnel will total about 100 observers and 50 members of a
support group to supervise the departure of the Contras.
</TEXT>
