<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BuildingCollapse     09-09 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Building Collapse,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platform Collapses, Killing One and Injuring Seven</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A balcony collapsed on workers sorting fruit
at a packing plant Friday afternoon, killing a woman and injuring
seven other people, authorities said.
   ``It caved in like a wedge, right where everybody was sitting,''
said fire Lt. Al Chronister.
   Five workers, including the woman who died, were trapped beneath
debris at the Hansen Fruit Co. until fire department rescue crews
freed them, Chronister said.
   Chronister estimated that the balcony, which was built into a
wall of the cavernous concrete building, weighed several tons. The
portion that collapsed measured 15-by-15 feet.
   Firefighters continued looking through the rubble, but Chronister
said it was unlikely anyone else was beneath the packing boxes,
fruit sorting trays, wooden pallets and other debris that came
tumbling down.
   At least 60 employees were in the plant, said Barb Dunn of the
state Department of Labor and Industries in Olympia.
   The injured were taken to St. Elizabeth's Medical Center and
Yakima Valley Memorial Hospital. The injuries included a broken arm,
head lacerations and minor cuts and bruises, hospital officials
said. Three victims were listed in serious condition.
   A pregnant woman who suffered bumps on the head and leg was taken
to Yakima Valley Memorial's maternity floor for observation, but was
in good condition.
   One firefighter suffered heat exhaustion, Chronister said.
   The dead woman's name was withheld pending notification of
relatives.
   Ms. Dunn said the cause of the collapse was not known, and the
state agency will investigate.
   The fatality was the first in Washington's fruit-packing industry
since the early 1970s, when record-keeping on accidents began, Ms.
Dunn said.
</TEXT>
