<FIRST>r a AM-Shrimpers-Protests     09-09 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shrimpers-Protests,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Blockade Waterways Along Louisiana Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shrimpers blockaded boat traffic Friday to
protest federal requirements that they use turtle-protecting devices
in their nets, and apparently won a promise from visiting President
Bush to review the rules.
   The Coast Guard said 37 vessels up to 100 feet long participated
in the daylong blockade of an industrial waterway near this Gulf
Coast city, but protesters put the number of boats at 50 to 100.
   At one point, 30 vessels were waiting to pass through the
blockade, said Chief Petty Officer Glenn LaMont.
   The protest ended at 5 p.m. after the Coast Guard relayed word
from Rep. Billy Tauzin, D-La., that Bush, who was visiting New
Orleans about 50 miles north of here, had agreed to review the
regulations.
   In a meeting with Tauzin and Reps. Lindy Boggs, D-La., and Bob
Livingston, R-La., Bush promised a review of regulations concerning
turtle excluder devices, or TEDS, Tauzin said in a news release.
   The congressman said White House Chief of Staff John Sununu would
meet with Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher ``and will hopefully
reach an acceptable balance between the need to conserve endangered
turtle species and allow shrimpers to stay in business.''
   Shrimpers and their supporters in Congress have succeeded in the
past in having TED rules delayed for weeks and sometimes months at a
time. Shrimpers also organized blockades in protest in July.
   About 500 shrimpers from Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and
Florida lined the motorcade route used by Bush during his visit
Friday morning.
   No arrests were made and no violence was reported during the
protest, said Coast Guard Cmdr. William Loeftstedt.
   Another 30 to 40 shrimpers blocked the Intracoastal Waterway near
Intracoastal City, La., said Chief Petty Officer Glenn LaMont. No
arrests or violence was reported.
   The blockaders ``were violating the law and those who violate it
could find themselves in trouble if they persist,'' Loeftstedt said.
   Blockading vessels were warned throughout the day to clear a
passage or the vessels could be boarded and crews arrested, said
Cmdr. Dave Smith.
   The Coast Guard gathered names and boat registration numbers of
the protesters. No decision was made on whether to charge them, but
the shrimpers could face civil fines of up to $25,000 if charged,
Loeftstedt said.
   Several angry shrimpers were glad to have the president's ear but
said they were only willing to wait a short while for new rules.
   ``Right now, shrimpers are in a no-win situation,'' said Randy
Adams, captain of the Sunshine Lady. ``They change the rules every
three minutes, and you can't win with any of them. If you pull a
TED, you can't make any money. If you don't, you get fined.''
   Designed to keep endangered sea turtles from being snared and
drowned in shrimp nets, TEDs are cage-like devices with trap doors
and slats designed to deflect turtles out of the nets while
preserving the shrimp catch.
   Shrimpers, however, claim they lose large amounts of shrimp
because of the TEDs, and say they can't afford to operate with them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
