<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-EmptyPlains Adv13   09-09 1211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Empty Plains, Adv 13,1243</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Sept. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Give Great Plains Back to the Buffalo, They Propose</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Deborah Epstein Popper and Frank Popper
weren't from New Jersey, it might be easier to win converts to their
notion that the Great Plains ought to be emptied of people and given
back to the buffalo and the tall grasses.
   But the Poppers are professors at Rutgers University in New
Jersey, a state that is the butt of more than a few jokes, and that
makes them easy targets for more of the same.
   Prominent among their critics is Rep. Pat Roberts, a Republican
who represents most of western Kansas, and who says that every time
the region goes through hard times ``you get another think-tank
effort to send us back to the buffalo.''
   ``We still believe Woody Allen was joking when he claimed every
place has redeeming social value `with the possible exception of New
Jersey,''' the congressman wrote to The Washington Post. ``We only
hope the Poppers were joking as well.''
   The Fargo Forum in North Dakota suggested in an editorial that
instead of letting the Plains slip back into grasslands, New Jersey
might be turned into a vast gasoline storage area.
   A Montana paper suggested paving over the Garden State.
   The High Plains Journal of Dodge City, Kan., called the plan ``a
real buffalo pie in the sky idea.'' And Mike Hayden, governor of
Kansas, said, ``I can only conclude their suggestions were in jest.''
   Not at all. The Poppers _ he's Harvard-educated, originally from
Chicago, and teaches urban studies; she's from New York, did
graduate work at Rutgers and teaches geography _ are serious.
   ``We believe that over the next generation the Plains will, as a
result of the largest, longest-running agricultural and
environmental miscalculation in America, become almost totally
depopulated,'' they wrote in Planning magazine, published by the
American Planning Association.
   It was a historic mistake, they say, to break the sod _ a process
started by the 1862 Homestead Act, which gave 160 acres to anyone
who would settle the land and stay five years.
   The Plains, they say, are inhospitable to agriculture and subject
to dust bowls, windstorms and droughts that will only worsen as the
water table falls.
   ``Endlessly windswept, nearly treeless, semiarid, austerely
beautiful, historically untenable, increasingly empty and now facing
ecological devastation,'' almost all of the area from the 98th
meridian west to the Rockies ultimately will become deserted, the
Poppers predict.
   The only question, they say, is whether the process will be eased
through government intervention or imposed brutally by raw market
forces.
   In an interview, Popper argued that without subsidies the Plains
cannot sustain agricultural life and ``as Gramm-Rudman kicks in it
is not going to make sense to keep subsidizing agriculture when what
the Plains produce mostly adds to national farm surpluses that are
already too big.''
   So instead, they propose letting the government gradually buy
back farmland ``and tear down the fences, replant the shortgrass and
restock the animals, including many bison _ creating what we would
call the Buffalo Commons.''
   They figure in 20 to 30 years vegetation and wildlife could
``reassert themselves'' and the Plains would be restored ``to their
pre-white condition.''
   ``We're not talking about some awful rural version of urban
renewal,'' says Potter. ``We're talking about a long-term,
demographic-economic evolution that would occur regardless of
whatever government does, an evolution that is market driven.''
   Vast areas are involved. The Poppers are talking about a third to
half the area of 10 states: most of the Dakotas, the western
two-thirds of Nebraska, the western halves of Kansas, Oklahoma and
Texas, the eastern tips of New Mexico and Colorado, eastern Wyoming
and all but westernmost Montana.
   ``The only way to keep the Plains from turning into an utter
wasteland, an American Empty Quarter, will be for the federal
government to step in and buy the land _ in short, to deprivatize
it,'' the Poppers wrote.
   Small ``service center'' cities such as Bismarck, N.D., and
Cheyenne, Wyo., or towns near interstate highways might stay in
business. So would locales able to sustain themselves through
agriculture, energy development or tourism _ but they're few, the
Poppers say.
   ``The Buffalo Commons will become the world's largest historic
preservation project, the ultimate national park,'' they wrote.
``Much of the Great Plains will become what all of the United States
once was _ a vast land mass, largely empty and unexploited.''
   Mrs. Popper says she's been overwhelmed by the reaction to their
article; the idea ``certainly has struck a nerve.''
   And ``even the people who say we are crazy,'' she says, usually
concede the area has serious problems.
   ``The government is not looking for new ways to spend money,''
Mrs. Popper says. ``We see this happening only after greater
devastation, greater catastrophe.''
   Adds Popper: ``We would like not to see it happen. We both like
the Great Plains. If our proposal is able to prevent this disaster
from occurring, we'd be delighted.''
   For all their Plains states critics, some there acknowledge the
Poppers have hit upon a home truth.
   ``I agree with Frank that it was a miscalculation when the social
engineers put as many people as they did out here through that
Homestead Act,'' says rancher Jim Strain of Rapid City, S.D., who
runs the American Cowman's Association.
   ``But I don't agree it should be a Buffalo Commons. I think it
was meant to be a vast grasslands for producers of red-meat animals
to graze their herds on. It was a mistake to plow this land with its
limited topsoil and limited moisture. The natural grasses which
nature had matched to the soil types preserved the soil and they had
a natural value, which is grazing.''
   In their hearts, would his fellow Plains people agree?
   ``It would be a 50-50 split,'' says Strain. ``There are people
who make some pretty good bucks out of this government
intervention.''
   Mark Lapping, dean of architecture at Kansas State University,
says the Poppers are wrong about one thing: ``Deprivitization is
something that will not happen.''
   He adds: ``There will always be some very large islands of
population and economic activity. While we see depopulatization of
many small towns, we're seeing the creation of many larger and
economically viable regions. ... Those people are not moving to
Washington or Kansas City but to Garden City and Liberal and
Manhattan and Lawrence and other places that have sufficient scale
and diversity.''
   And geographer Bret Wallach of the University of Oklahoma said
the Poppers are ``a bit quixotic in the short term but in the long
run it is an idea whose time will probably come.''
   ``This country probably has a lot more cropland than in the long
run it will need and we ouight to think about what to do with it,''
Wallach says.
   ``Countries in the Third World are going to be able to take care
of themselves one of these days,'' he says. ``In New England they
let the farmland grow back into trees and maybe that is the
enlightened thing to do _ restore it to its virgin use.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Sept. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
