<FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 0252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Campeau Adv10   09-09 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Campeau, Adv 10,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Sept. 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Planned Bloomie's Sale Dashes Campeau Hopes for Real Estate-Retailing
Empire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Campeau was on top of the world a year and
a-half ago, gloating after his victory in the two-month-long battle
for Federated Department Stores Inc.
   The real estate developer, who already had Allied Stores Corp.
among his holdings, had dreams of a real estate and retailing
empire, with the crown jewel of department store chains,
Bloomingdale's, giving him an entree into new shopping malls in
untapped markets.
   But those dreams are all but shattered now as Campeau, unable to
handle his company's massive debt as the retail business soured, has
been forced to put his prize chain on the block.
   ``Bloomingdale's would be the last thing he would want to sell,''
Walter Loeb, a retail industry analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
Inc., said of Campeau last week.
   But Campeau has no choice but to sell: He faces an estimated $450
million loan payment that is coming due, he doesn't have the cash on
hand to pay it and selling the coveted Bloomie's is the fastest way
to get that cash.
   In a statement Friday announcing Campeau's plans to sell the
chain and undertake a financial restructuring, the developer's
holding company, Campeau Corp., tried to put the best face on what
could only be called a defeat:
   ``Following the Bloomingdale's divestiture, Federated and Allied
will continue to be a major force in U.S. retailing ...''
   Campeau will still own 240 department stores, including Allied's
The Bon, Jordan Marsh, Maas Brothers and Stern's stores and
Federated's Abraham &amp; Straus, Burdine's, Goldsmith's, Lazarus and
Rich's chains. But without Bloomingdale's _ now a part of Federated
_ he will not have the same influence in shopping center development
that he had hoped to possess.
   And, the forced sale of Bloomingdale's is a black mark on his
financial reputation.
   Robert Campeau was a virtually unknown Canadian developer when,
in late 1986, he launched a hostile bid for Allied. He won the
company, paying $3.4 billion, and then began to unload most of
Allied's store units to help pay off his bank loans.
   In January 1988, just a year after closing on the Allied deal, he
began his run at Federated. Campeau found himself in a bidding war
with R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc., one that drove up the price for the
company until Campeau ended up paying $6.6 billion for the
retailer's shares, and a total of $8.8 billion for the entire
company once costs were figured in.
   That price is what did Campeau in.
   ``They paid too much for it,'' said Pamela Stubing, an analyst
with Moody's Investors Service.
   Campeau took over staggering bank loans and sold billions of
dollars in junk bonds to finance his deals. He also sold off
billions of dollars in assets, leaving only department stores _ and
their valuable real estate _ in his retail portfolio.
   He was depending on the stores to generate enough cash flow to
pay the debt, but the stagnant consumer spending climate has taken a
larger toll on sales than he expected.
   ``They were optimistic in the early part of the year, looking for
a 5 to 6 percent increase in sales, but that might not have come
true in the second quarter,'' said Edward Johnson, an analyst with
Prescott Ball &amp; Turben.
   Campeau is not the only developer-turned-retailer to run into
problems. L.J. Hooker Corp., which owns the Bonwit Teller and B.
Altman chains in the United States, has run into financial problems
in its home country, Australia, and its retail operations here have
suffered as well.
   Hooker's U.S. subsidiary was forced to file for protection under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code in New York.
   Analysts say developers have bitten off more than they could chew.
   ``Developers should never have taken on this kind of debt,''
given the uncertain nature of retailing, Morgan Stanley's Loeb said.
   Ms. Stubing agreed. Developers ``look on the properties as an
asset, but it's a working asset and it's only valuable if you make
money from it,'' she said.
   ``Though they knew the value (of the real estate), they didn't
know what they could get from it with the cash flow,'' she said.
   When Campeau bought Federated, the retailing industry was already
mired in a sales slump. The developer claimed that he had factored a
continuation of the downturn into his plans.
   Johnson said increasing competition from stores like the booming
Nordstrom chain has hurt the big department stores.
   Another problem Campeau has faced _ and likely caused _ is the
high management turnover since the chains were acquired. Several
high-level executives at Campeau Corp. and the retail companies have
come and gone in the past two years, and this has not helped matters.
   ``Whenever you have changes at the top continuing, it puts
adverse pressure on the management underneath,'' Johnson said.
   If the developers have good retail management, they have a better
chance of succeeding, but ``if they're looking to pyramid the
profits'' without trying to run a solid merchandising operation,
they can't get the cash flow they need, Johnson said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Sept. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
